# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: enzymology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:enzymology/active-site] In biology and biochemistry, the **active site** is the region of an enzyme where substrate molecules bind and undergo a chemical reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The active site consists of amino acid residues that form temporary bonds with the substrate, the *binding site*, and residues that catalyse a reaction of that substrate, the ***catalytic site***.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Although the active site occupies only ~10–20% of the volume of an enzyme, it is the most important part as it directly catalyzes the chemical reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It usually consists of three to four amino acids, while other amino acids within the protein are required to maintain the tertiary structure of the enzymes.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Each active site is evolved to be optimised to bind a particular substrate and catalyse a particular reaction, resulting in high specificity.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This specificity is determined by the arrangement of amino acids within the active site and the structure of the substrates.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Sometimes enzymes also need to bind with some cofactors to fulfil their function.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The active site is usually a groove or pocket of the enzyme which can be located in a deep tunnel within the enzyme, or between the interfaces of multimeric enzymes.
[src:enzymology/active-site] An active site can catalyse a reaction repeatedly as residues are not altered at the end of the reaction (they may change during the reaction, but are regenerated by the end).
[src:enzymology/active-site] This process is achieved by lowering the activation energy of the reaction, so more substrates have enough energy to undergo reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Usually, an enzyme molecule has only one active site, and the active site fits with one specific type of substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] An active site contains a binding site that binds the substrate and orients it for catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The orientation of the substrate and the close proximity between it and the active site is so important that in some cases the enzyme can still function properly even though all other parts are mutated and lose function.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Initially, the interaction between the active site and the substrate is non-covalent and transient.
[src:enzymology/active-site] There are four important types of interaction that hold the substrate in a defined orientation and form an enzyme-substrate complex (ES complex): hydrogen bonds, van der Waals interactions, hydrophobic interactions and electrostatic force interactions.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The charge distribution on the substrate and active site must be complementary, which means all positive and negative charges must be cancelled out.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Otherwise, there will be a repulsive force pushing them apart.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The active site usually contains non-polar amino acids, although sometimes polar amino acids may also occur.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The binding of substrate to the binding site requires at least three contact points in order to achieve stereo-, regio-, and enantioselectivity.
[src:enzymology/active-site] For example, alcohol dehydrogenase which catalyses the transfer of a hydride ion from ethanol to NAD+ interacts with the substrate methyl group, hydroxyl group and the pro-*(R)* hydrogen that will be abstracted during the reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In order to exert their function, enzymes need to assume their correct protein fold (*native fold*) and tertiary structure.
[src:enzymology/active-site] To maintain this defined three-dimensional structure, proteins rely on various types of interactions between their amino acid residues.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If these interactions are interfered with, for example by extreme pH values, high temperature or high ion concentrations, this will cause the enzyme to denature and lose its catalytic activity.
[src:enzymology/active-site] A tighter fit between an active site and the substrate molecule is believed to increase the efficiency of a reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If the tightness between the active site of DNA polymerase and its substrate is increased, the fidelity, which means the correct rate of DNA replication will also increase.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Most enzymes have deeply buried active sites, which can be accessed by a substrate via access channels.
[src:enzymology/active-site] There are three proposed models of how enzymes fit their specific substrate: the lock and key model, the induced fit model, and the conformational selection model.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The latter two are not mutually exclusive: conformational selection can be followed by a change in the enzyme's shape.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Additionally, a protein may not wholly follow either model.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Amino acids at the binding site of ubiquitin generally follow the induced fit model, whereas the rest of the protein generally adheres to conformational selection.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Factors such as temperature likely influences the pathway taken during binding, with higher temperatures predicted to increase the importance of conformational selection and decrease that of induced fit.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This concept was suggested by the 19th-century chemist Emil Fischer.
[src:enzymology/active-site] He proposed that the active site and substrate are two stable structures that fit perfectly without any further modification, just like a key fits into a lock.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If one substrate perfectly binds to its active site, the interactions between them will be strongest, resulting in high catalytic efficiency.
[src:enzymology/active-site] As time went by, limitations of this model started to appear.
[src:enzymology/active-site] For example, the competitive enzyme inhibitor methylglucoside can bind tightly to the active site of 4-alpha-glucanotransferase and perfectly fits into it.
[src:enzymology/active-site] However, 4-alpha-glucanotransferase is not active on methylglucoside and no glycosyl transfer occurs.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The Lock and Key hypothesis cannot explain this, as it would predict a high efficiency of methylglucoside glycosyl transfer due to its tight binding.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Apart from competitive inhibition, this theory cannot explain the mechanism of action of non-competitive inhibitors either, as they do not bind to the active site but nevertheless influence catalytic activity.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Daniel Koshland's theory of enzyme-substrate binding is that the active site and the binding portion of the substrate are not exactly complementary.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The induced fit model is a development of the lock-and-key model and assumes that an active site is flexible and changes shape until the substrate is completely bound.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This model is similar to a person wearing a glove: the glove changes shape to fit the hand.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The enzyme initially has a conformation that attracts its substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Enzyme surface is flexible and only the correct catalyst can induce interaction leading to catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Conformational changes may then occur as the substrate is bound.
[src:enzymology/active-site] After the reaction products will move away from the enzyme and the active site returns to its initial shape.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This hypothesis is supported by the observation that the entire protein domain could move several nanometers during catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This movement of protein surface can create microenvironments that favour the catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This model suggests that enzymes exist in a variety of conformations, only some of which are capable of binding to a substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] When a substrate is bound to the protein, the equilibrium in the conformational ensemble shifts towards those able to bind ligands (as enzymes with bound substrates are removed from the equilibrium between the free conformations).
[src:enzymology/active-site] Positively charged sodium ion and negatively charged fluoride ion attract each other to form sodium fluoride under electrostatic interaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Hydrogen bond between two water molecules.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Van der Waals force between two acetone molecules.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The lower acetone molecule contains a partially negative oxygen atom that attracts partially positive carbon atom in the upper acetone.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Hydrophobic and hydrophilic groups tend to assemble with the same kind of molecules.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Once the substrate is bound and oriented to the active site, catalysis can begin.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The residues of the catalytic site are typically very close to the binding site, and some residues can have dual-roles in both binding and catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] During enzyme catalytic reaction, the substrate and active site are brought together in a close proximity.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Firstly, when substrates bind within the active site the effective concentration of it significantly increases than in solution.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This means the number of substrate molecules involved in the reaction is also increased.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This process also reduces the desolvation energy required for the reaction to occur.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In solution substrate molecules are surrounded by solvent molecules and energy is required for enzyme molecules to replace them and contact with the substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Since bulk molecules can be excluded from the active site this energy output can be minimised.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Next, the active site is designed to reorient the substrate to reduce the activation energy for the reaction to occur.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The alignment of the substrate, after binding, is locked in a high energy state and can proceed to the next step.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In addition, this binding is favoured by entropy as the energy cost associated with solution reaction is largely eliminated since solvent cannot enter active site.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In the end, the active site may manipulate the Molecular orbital of the substrate into a suitable orientation to reduce activation energy.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The electrostatic states of substrate and active site must be complementary to each other.
[src:enzymology/active-site] A polarized negatively charged amino acid side chain will repel uncharged substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] But if the transition state involves the formation of an ion centre then the side chain will now produce a favourable interaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Many enzymes including serine protease, cysteine protease, protein kinase and phosphatase evolved to form transient covalent bonds between them and their substrates to lower the activation energy and allow the reaction to occur.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This process can be divided into 2 steps: formation and breakdown.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The former step is rate-limit step while the later step is needed to regenerate intact enzyme.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Metal ions have multiple roles during the reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Firstly it can bind to negatively charged substrate groups so they will not repel electron pairs from active site's nucleophilic groups.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It can attract negatively charged electrons to increase electrophilicity.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It can also bridge between active site and substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] At last, they may change the conformational structure of the substrate to favour reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In some reactions, protons and hydroxide may directly act as acid and base in term of specific acid and specific base catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] But more often groups in substrate and active site act as Brønsted–Lowry acid and base.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This is called general acid and general base theory.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The easiest way to distinguish between them is to check whether the reaction rate is determined by the concentrations of the general acid and base.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If the answer is yes then the reaction is the general type.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Since most enzymes have an optimum pH of 6 to 7, the amino acids in the side chain usually have a p*K*a of 4~10.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Candidate include aspartate, glutamate, histidine, cysteine.
[src:enzymology/active-site] These acids and bases can stabilise the nucleophile or electrophile formed during the catalysis by providing positive and negative charges.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Quantitative studies of enzymatic reactions often found that the acceleration of chemical reaction speed cannot be fully explained by existing theories like the approximation, acid/base catalysis and electrophile/nucleophile catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] And there is an obvious paradox: in reversible enzymatic reaction if the active site perfectly fits the substrates then the backward reaction will be slowed since products cannot fit perfectly into the active site.
[src:enzymology/active-site] So conformational distortion was introduced and argues that both active site and substrate can undergo conformational changes to fit with each other all the time.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This theory is a little similar to the Lock and Key Theory, but at this time the active site is preprogrammed to bind perfectly to substrate in transition state rather than in ground state.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The formation of transition state within the solution requires a large amount of energy to relocate solvent molecules and the reaction is slowed.
[src:enzymology/active-site] So the active site can substitute solvent molecules and surround the substrates to minimize the counterproductive effect imposed by the solution.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The presence of charged groups with the active site will attract substrates and ensure electrostatic complementarity.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In reality, most enzyme mechanisms involve a combination of several different types of catalysis.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The role of glutathione(GSH) is to remove accumulated reactive oxygen species which may damage cells.
[src:enzymology/active-site] During this process, its thiol side chain is oxidised and two glutathione molecules are connected by a disulphide bond to form a dimer(GSSG).
[src:enzymology/active-site] In order to regenerate glutathione the disulphide bond has to be broken, In human cells, this is done by glutathione reductase(GR).
[src:enzymology/active-site] Glutathione reductase is a dimer that contains two identical subunits.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It requires one NADP and one FAD as the cofactors.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The active site is located in the linkage between two subunits.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The NADPH is involved in the generation of FADH-.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In the active site, there are two cysteine residues besides the FAD cofactor and are used to break the disulphide bond during the catalytic reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] NADPH is bound by three positively charged residues: Arg-218, His-219 and Arg-224.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The catalytic process starts when the FAD is reduced by NADPH to accept one electron and from FADH−.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It then attacks the disulphide bond formed between 2 cysteine residues, forming one SH bond and a single S− group.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This S− group will act as a nucleophile to attack the disulphide bond in the oxidised glutathione(GSSG), breaking it and forming a cysteine-SG complex.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The first SG− anion is released and then receives one proton from adjacent SH group and from the first glutathione monomer.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Next the adjacent S− group attack disulphide bond in cysteine-SG complex and release the second SG− anion.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It receives one proton in solution and forms the second glutathione monomer.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Chymotrypsin is a serine endopeptidase that is present in pancreatic juice and helps the hydrolysis of proteins and peptide.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It catalyzes the hydrolysis of peptide bonds in L-isomers of tyrosine, phenylalanine, and tryptophan.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In the active site of this enzyme, three amino acid residues work together to form a catalytic triad which makes up the catalytic site.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In chymotrypsin, these residues are Ser-195, His-57 and Asp-102.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The mechanism of chymotrypsin can be divided into two phases.
[src:enzymology/active-site] First, Ser-195 nucleophilically attacks the peptide bond carbon in the substrate to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The nucleophilicity of Ser-195 is enhanced by His-57, which abstracts a proton from Ser-195 and is in turn stabilised by the negatively charged carboxylate group (RCOO−) in Asp-102.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Furthermore, the tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate generated in this step is stabilised by hydrogen bonds from Ser-195 and Gly-193.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In the second stage, the R'NH group is protonated by His-57 to form R'NH2 and leaves the intermediate, leaving behind the acylated Ser-195.
[src:enzymology/active-site] His-57 then acts as a base again to abstract one proton from a water molecule.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The resulting hydroxide anion nucleophilically attacks the acyl-enzyme complex to form a second tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate, which is once again stabilised by H bonds.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In the end, Ser-195 leaves the tetrahedral intermediate, breaking the CO bond that connected the enzyme to the peptide substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] A proton is transferred to Ser-195 through His-57, so that all three amino acid return to their initial state.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Substrate unbinding is influenced by various factors.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Larger ligands generally stay in the active site longer, as do those with more rotatable bonds (although this may be a side effect of size).
[src:enzymology/active-site] When the solvent is excluded from the active site, less flexible proteins result in longer residence times.
[src:enzymology/active-site] More hydrogen bonds shielded from the solvent also decrease unbinding.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Enzymes can use cofactors as 'helper molecules'.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Coenzymes are referred to those non-protein molecules that bind with enzymes to help them fulfill their jobs.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Mostly they are connected to the active site by non-covalent bonds such as hydrogen bond or hydrophobic interaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] But sometimes a covalent bond can also form between them.
[src:enzymology/active-site] For example, the heme in cytochrome C is bound to the protein through thioester bond.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In some occasions, coenzymes can leave enzymes after the reaction is finished.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Otherwise, they permanently bind to the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Coenzyme is a broad concept which includes metal ions, various vitamins and ATP.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If an enzyme needs coenzyme to work itself, it is called an apoenzyme.
[src:enzymology/active-site] In fact, it alone cannot catalyze reactions properly.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Only when its cofactor comes in and binds to the active site to form holoenzyme does it work properly.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It contains a distinct conjugated isoalloxazine ring system.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Flavin has multiple redox states and can be used in processes that involve the transfer of one or two electrons.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It can act as an electron acceptor in reaction, like the oxidation of NAD to NADH, to accept two electrons and form 1,5-dihydroflavin.
[src:enzymology/active-site] On the other hand, it can form semiquinone(free radical) by accepting one electron, and then converts to fully reduced form by the addition of an extra electron.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This property allows it to be used in one electron oxidation process.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Inhibitors disrupt the interaction between enzyme and substrate, slowing down the rate of a reaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] There are different types of inhibitor, including both reversible and irreversible forms.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Competitive inhibitors are inhibitors that only target free enzyme molecules.
[src:enzymology/active-site] They compete with substrates for free enzyme acceptor and can be overcome by increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Competitive inhibitors usually have structural similarities to the substrates and or ES complex.
[src:enzymology/active-site] As a result, they can fit into the active site and trigger favourable interactions to fill in the space and block substrates from entry.
[src:enzymology/active-site] They can also induce transient conformational changes in the active site so substrates cannot fit perfectly with it.
[src:enzymology/active-site] After a short period of time, competitive inhibitors will drop off and leave the enzyme intact.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Inhibitors are classified as non-competitive inhibitors when they bind both free enzyme and ES complex.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Since they do not compete with substrates for the active site, they cannot be overcome by simply increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:enzymology/active-site] They usually bind to a different site on the enzyme and alter the 3-dimensional structure of the active site to block substrates from entry or leaving the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Irreversible inhibitors are similar to competitive inhibitors as they both bind to the active site.
[src:enzymology/active-site] However, irreversible inhibitors form irreversible covalent bonds with the amino acid residues in the active site and never leave.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Therefore, the active site is occupied and the substrate cannot enter.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Occasionally the inhibitor will leave but the catalytic site is permanently altered in shape.
[src:enzymology/active-site] These inhibitors usually contain electrophilic groups like halogen substitutes and epoxides.
[src:enzymology/active-site] As time goes by more and more enzymes are bound by irreversible inhibitors and cannot function anymore.
[src:enzymology/active-site] HIV protease inhibitors are used to treat patients having AIDS virus by preventing its DNA replication.
[src:enzymology/active-site] HIV protease is used by the virus to cleave Gag-Pol polyprotein into 3 smaller proteins that are responsible for virion assembly, package and maturation.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This enzyme targets the specific phenylalanine-proline cleave site within the target protein.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If HIV protease is switched off the virion particle will lose function and cannot infect patients.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Since it is essential in viral replication and is absent in healthy human, it is an ideal target for drug development.
[src:enzymology/active-site] HIV protease belongs to aspartic protease family and has a similar mechanism.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Firstly the aspartate residue activates a water molecule and turns it into a nucleophile.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Then it attacks the carbonyl group within the peptide bond (NH-CO) to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The nitrogen atom within the intermediate receives a proton, forming an amide group and subsequent rearrangement leads to the breakdown of the bond between it and the intermediate and forms two products.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Inhibitors usually contain a nonhydrolyzable hydroxyethylene or hydroxyethylamine groups that mimic the tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Since they share a similar structure and electrostatic arrangement to the transition state of substrates they can still fit into the active site but cannot be broken down, so hydrolysis cannot occur.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Strychnine is a neurotoxin that causes death by affecting nerves that control muscular contraction and cause respiration difficulty.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The impulse is transmitted between the synapse through a neurotransmitter called acetylcholine.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It is released into the synapse between nerve cells and binds to receptors in the postsynaptic cell.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Then an action potential is generated and transmitted through the postsynaptic cell to start a new cycle.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Glycine can inhibit the activity of neurotransmitter receptors, thus a larger amount of acetylcholinesterase is required to trigger an action potential.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This makes sure that the generation of nerve impulses is tightly controlled.
[src:enzymology/active-site] However, this control is broken down when strychnine is added.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It inhibits glycine receptors(a chloride channel) and a much lower level of neurotransmitter concentration can trigger an action potential.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Nerves now constantly transmit signals and cause excessive muscular contraction, leading to asphyxiation and death.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Diisopropyl fluorophosphate (DIFP) is an irreversible inhibitor that blocks the action of serine protease.
[src:enzymology/active-site] When it binds to the enzyme a nucleophilic substitution reaction occurs and releases one hydrogen fluoride molecule.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The OH group in the active site acts as a nucleophile to attack the phosphorus in DIFP and form a tetrahedral intermediate and release a proton.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Then the P-F bond is broken, one electron is transferred to the F atom and it leaves the intermediate as F− anion.
[src:enzymology/active-site] It combines with a proton in solution to form one HF molecule.
[src:enzymology/active-site] A covalent bond formed between the active site and DIFP, so the serine side chain is no longer available to the substrate.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Identification of active sites is crucial in the process of drug discovery.
[src:enzymology/active-site] The 3-D structure of the enzyme is analysed to identify active site residues and design drugs which can fit into them.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Proteolytic enzymes are targets for some drugs, such as protease inhibitors, which include drugs against AIDS and hypertension.
[src:enzymology/active-site] These protease inhibitors bind to an enzyme's active site and block interaction with natural substrates.
[src:enzymology/active-site] An important factor in drug design is the strength of binding between the active site and an enzyme inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If the enzyme found in bacteria is significantly different from the human enzyme then an inhibitor can be designed against that particular bacterium without harming the human enzyme.
[src:enzymology/active-site] If one kind of enzyme is only present in one kind of organism, its inhibitor can be used to specifically wipe them out.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Active sites can be mapped to aid the design of new drugs such as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This involves the description of the size of an active site and the number and properties of sub-sites, such as details of the binding interaction.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Modern database technology called CPASS (Comparison of Protein Active Site Structures) however allows the comparison of active sites in more detail and the finding of structural similarity using software.
[src:enzymology/active-site] An allosteric site is a site on an enzyme, unrelated to its active site, which can bind an effector molecule.
[src:enzymology/active-site] This interaction is another mechanism of enzyme regulation.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Allosteric modification usually happens in proteins with more than one subunit.
[src:enzymology/active-site] Allosteric interactions are often present in metabolic pathways and are beneficial in that they allow one step of a reaction to regulate another step.
[src:enzymology/active-site] They allow an enzyme to have a range of molecular interactions, other than the highly specific active site.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] A **cofactor** is a non-protein chemical compound or metallic ion that is required for an enzyme's role as a catalyst.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be considered "helper molecules" that assist in biochemical transformations.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The rates at which these happen are characterized in an area of study called enzyme kinetics.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors typically differ from ligands in that they often derive their function by remaining bound.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be classified into two types: inorganic ions and complex organic molecules called coenzymes.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Coenzymes are mainly derived from vitamins and other organic essential nutrients in small amounts (some definitions limit the use of the term "cofactor" for inorganic substances; both types are included here).
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Coenzymes are further divided into two types.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The first is called a "prosthetic group", which consists of a coenzyme that is tightly (or even covalently and, therefore, permanently) bound to a protein.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The second type of coenzymes are called "cosubstrates", and are transiently bound to the protein.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Cosubstrates may be released from a protein at some point, and then rebind later.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Both prosthetic groups and cosubstrates have the same function, which is to facilitate the reaction of enzymes and proteins.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] An inactive enzyme without the cofactor is called an apoenzyme, while the complete enzyme with cofactor is called a holoenzyme.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Some enzymes or enzyme complexes require several cofactors.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are often vitamins or made from vitamins.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Many contain the nucleotide adenosine monophosphate (AMP) as part of their structures, such as ATP, coenzyme A, FAD, and NAD+.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This common structure may reflect a common evolutionary origin as part of ribozymes in an ancient RNA world.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] It has been suggested that the AMP part of the molecule can be considered to be a kind of "handle" by which the enzyme can "grasp" the coenzyme to switch it between different catalytic centers.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be divided into two major groups: **organic** **cofactors**, such as flavin or heme; and **inorganic cofactors**, such as the metal ions Mg2+, Zn2+, Cu+, Mn2+ and iron–sulfur clusters.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are sometimes further divided into *coenzymes* and *prosthetic groups*.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The term coenzyme refers specifically to enzymes and, as such, to the functional properties of a protein.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] On the other hand, "prosthetic group" emphasizes the nature of the binding of a cofactor to a protein (tight or covalent) and, thus, refers to a structural property.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Different sources give slightly different definitions of coenzymes, cofactors, and prosthetic groups.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Some consider tightly bound organic molecules as prosthetic groups and not as coenzymes, while others define all non-protein organic molecules needed for enzyme activity as coenzymes, and classify those that are tightly bound as coenzyme prosthetic groups.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] A 1980 letter in *Trends in Biochemistry Sciences* noted the confusion in the literature and the essentially arbitrary distinction made between prosthetic groups and coenzymes group and proposed the following scheme.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Here, cofactors were defined as an additional substance apart from protein and substrate that is required for enzyme activity and a prosthetic group as a substance that undergoes its whole catalytic cycle attached to a single enzyme molecule.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] However, the author could not arrive at a single all-encompassing definition of a "coenzyme" and proposed that this term be dropped from use in the literature.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The study of these cofactors falls under the area of bioinorganic chemistry.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In nutrition, the list of essential trace elements reflects their role as cofactors.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In humans this list commonly includes iron, magnesium, manganese, cobalt, copper, zinc, and molybdenum.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Although chromium deficiency causes impaired glucose tolerance, no human enzyme that uses this metal as a cofactor has been identified.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Iodine is also an essential trace element, but this element is used as part of the structure of thyroid hormones rather than as an enzyme cofactor.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Calcium is, therefore, a cell signaling ion, and not usually considered a cofactor of the enzymes it regulates.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In many cases, the cofactor includes both an inorganic and organic component.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] One diverse set of examples is the heme proteins, which consist of a porphyrin ring coordinated to iron.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Iron–sulfur clusters are complexes of iron and sulfur atoms held within proteins by cysteinyl residues.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] They play both structural and functional roles, including electron transfer, redox sensing, and as structural modules.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are small organic molecules (typically a molecular mass less than 1000 Da) that can be either loosely or tightly bound to the enzyme and directly participate in the reaction.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In the latter case, when it is difficult to remove without denaturing the enzyme, it can be called a prosthetic group.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] There is no sharp division between loosely and tightly bound cofactors.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Many such as NAD+ can be tightly bound in some enzymes, while it is loosely bound in others.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Another example is thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), which is tightly bound in transketolase or pyruvate decarboxylase, while it is less tightly bound in pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Other coenzymes, flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), biotin, and lipoamide, for instance, are tightly bound.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Tightly bound cofactors are, in general, regenerated during the same reaction cycle, while loosely bound cofactors can be regenerated in a subsequent reaction catalyzed by a different enzyme.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In the latter case, the cofactor can also be considered a substrate or cosubstrate.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Vitamins can serve as precursors to many organic cofactors (e.g., vitamins B1, B2, B6, B12, niacin, folic acid) or as coenzymes themselves (e.g., vitamin C).
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] However, vitamins do have other functions in the body.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Many organic cofactors also contain a nucleotide, such as the electron carriers NAD and FAD, and coenzyme A, which carries acyl groups.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Most of these cofactors are found in a huge variety of species, and some are universal to all forms of life.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] An exception to this wide distribution is a group of unique cofactors that evolved in methanogens, which are restricted to this group of archaea.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Although enzyme catalyzed industrial processes are highly efficient, some of the enzymes are dependent on nicotinamide cofactors (NADH/NAD+, NADP/NAPH).
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Due to the high price of such cofactors, these processes would not be economically competitive.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Recently, some synthetic organic compounds were identified as economically promising biomimetic counterparts of natural cofactors.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Metabolism involves a vast array of chemical reactions, but most fall under a few basic types of reactions that involve the transfer of functional groups.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This common chemistry allows cells to use a small set of metabolic intermediates to carry chemical groups between different reactions.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] These group-transfer intermediates are the loosely bound organic cofactors, often called coenzymes.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Each class of group-transfer reaction is carried out by a particular cofactor, which is the substrate for a set of enzymes that produce it, and a set of enzymes that consume it.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] An example of this are the dehydrogenases that use nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) as a cofactor.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Here, hundreds of separate types of enzymes remove electrons from their substrates and reduce NAD+ to NADH.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This reduced cofactor is then a substrate for any of the reductases in the cell that require electrons to reduce their substrates.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Therefore, these cofactors are continuously recycled as part of metabolism.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] As an example, the total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mole.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This ATP is constantly being broken down into ADP, and then converted back into ATP.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The energy used by human cells requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 moles of ATP daily, which is around 50 to 75 kg.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In typical situations, humans use up their body weight of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This means that each ATP molecule is recycled 1000 to 1500 times daily.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors, such as ATP and NADH, are present in all known forms of life and form a core part of metabolism.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Such universal conservation indicates that these molecules evolved very early in the development of living things.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] At least some of the current set of cofactors may, therefore, have been present in the last universal ancestor, which lived about 4 billion years ago.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors may have been present even earlier in the history of life on Earth.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The nucleotide adenosine is a cofactor for many basic metabolic enzymes such as transferases.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Adenosine-based cofactors may have acted as adaptors that allowed enzymes and ribozymes to bind new cofactors through small modifications in existing adenosine-binding domains, which had originally evolved to bind a different cofactor.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This process of adapting a pre-evolved structure for a novel use is known as *exaptation*.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The first organic cofactor to be discovered was NAD+, which was identified by Arthur Harden and William Young 1906.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] They noticed that adding boiled and filtered yeast extract greatly accelerated alcoholic fermentation in unboiled yeast extracts.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] They called the unidentified factor responsible for this effect a *coferment*.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Through a long and difficult purification from yeast extracts, this heat-stable factor was identified as a nucleotide sugar phosphate by Hans von Euler-Chelpin.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Other cofactors were identified throughout the early 20th century, with ATP being isolated in 1929 by Karl Lohmann, and coenzyme A being discovered in 1945 by Fritz Albert Lipmann.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The functions of these molecules were at first mysterious, but, in 1936, Otto Heinrich Warburg identified the function of NAD+ in hydride transfer.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This discovery was followed in the early 1940s by the work of Herman Kalckar, who established the link between the oxidation of sugars and the generation of ATP.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This confirmed the central role of ATP in energy transfer that had been proposed by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Later, in 1949, Morris Friedkin and Albert L.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Lehninger proved that NAD+ linked metabolic pathways such as the citric acid cycle and the synthesis of ATP.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In a number of enzymes, the moiety that acts as a cofactor is formed by post-translational modification of a part of the protein sequence.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This often replaces the need for an external binding factor, such as a metal ion, for protein function.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Potential modifications could be oxidation of aromatic residues, binding between residues, cleavage or ring-forming.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] These alterations are distinct from other post-translation protein modifications, such as phosphorylation, methylation, or glycosylation in that the amino acids typically acquire new functions.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] This increases the functionality of the protein; unmodified amino acids are typically limited to acid-base reactions, and the alteration of resides can give the protein electrophilic sites or the ability to stabilize free radicals.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Examples of cofactor production include tryptophan tryptophylquinone (TTQ), derived from two tryptophan side chains, and 4-methylidene-imidazole-5-one (MIO), derived from an Ala-Ser-Gly motif.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Characterization of protein-derived cofactors is conducted using X-ray crystallography and mass spectroscopy; structural data is necessary because sequencing does not readily identify the altered sites.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] The term is used in other areas of biology to refer more broadly to non-protein (or even protein) molecules that either activate, inhibit, or are required for the protein to function.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] For example, ligands such as hormones that bind to and activate receptor proteins are termed cofactors or coactivators, whereas molecules that inhibit receptor proteins are termed corepressors.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] One such example is the G protein-coupled receptor family of receptors, which are frequently found in sensory neurons.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] Ligand binding to the receptors activates the G protein, which then activates an enzyme to activate the effector.
[src:enzymology/cofactor-biochemistry] In order to avoid confusion, it has been suggested that such proteins that have ligand-binding mediated activation or repression be referred to as coregulators.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Most enzymes are made predominantly of proteins, either a single protein chain or many such chains in a multi-subunit complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes often also incorporate non-protein components, such as metal ions or specialized organic molecules known as cofactor (e.g. adenosine triphosphate).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Many cofactors are vitamins, and their role as vitamins is directly linked to their use in the catalysis of biological process within metabolism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Catalysis of biochemical reactions in the cell is vital since many but not all metabolically essential reactions have very low rates when uncatalysed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] One driver of protein evolution is the optimization of such catalytic activities, although only the most crucial enzymes operate near catalytic efficiency limits, and many enzymes are far from optimal.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Mechanisms of enzyme catalysis vary, but are all similar in principle to other types of chemical catalysis in that the crucial factor is a reduction of energy barrier(s) separating the reactants (or substrates) from the products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The reduction of activation energy (*E*a) increases the fraction of reactant molecules that can overcome this barrier and form the product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] An important principle is that since they only reduce energy barriers between products and reactants, enzymes always catalyze reactions in both directions, and cannot drive a reaction forward or affect the equilibrium position – only the speed with which is it achieved.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] As with other catalysts, the enzyme is not consumed or changed by the reaction (as a substrate is) but is recycled such that a single enzyme performs many rounds of catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes are often highly specific, i.e. they only act on particular substrates, sometimes only one.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Others show group specificity and can act on similar but not identical chemical groups such as peptide bonds.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Many enzymes have stereochemical specificity and act on one stereoisomer but not another.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The classic model for the enzyme-substrate interaction is the induced fit model.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This model proposes that the initial interaction between enzyme and substrate is relatively weak, but that these weak interactions rapidly induce conformational changes in the enzyme that strengthen binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The advantages of the induced fit mechanism arise due to the stabilizing effect of strong enzyme binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] There are two mechanisms of substrate binding: uniform binding, which has strong substrate binding, and differential binding, which has strong transition state binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The stabilizing effect of uniform binding increases both substrate and transition state binding affinity, while differential binding increases only transition state binding affinity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Both are used by enzymes and have been evolutionarily chosen to minimize the activation energy of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes that are saturated, that is, have a high affinity substrate binding, require differential binding to reduce the energy of activation, whereas small substrate unbound enzymes may use either differential or uniform binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] These effects have led to most proteins using the differential binding mechanism to reduce the energy of activation, so most substrates have high affinity for the enzyme while in the transition state.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Differential binding is carried out by the induced fit mechanism – the substrate first binds weakly, then the enzyme changes conformation increasing the affinity to the transition state and stabilizing it, so reducing the activation energy to reach it.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The induced fit concept cannot be used to rationalize catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] That is, the chemical catalysis is defined as the reduction of *E*a‡ (when the system is already in the ES‡) relative to *E*a‡ in the uncatalyzed reaction in water (without the enzyme).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The induced fit only suggests that the barrier is lower in the closed form of the enzyme but does not tell us what the reason for the barrier reduction is.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Induced fit may be beneficial to the fidelity of molecular recognition in the presence of competition and noise via the conformational proofreading mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, the role of induced fit in controlling replication fidelity has been questioned and remains poorly defined.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Experimental and theoretical analyses have suggested that induced fit alone does not provide a sufficient explanation for high replication fidelity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] These conformational changes also bring catalytic residues in the active site close to the chemical bonds in the substrate that will be altered in the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] After binding takes place, one or more mechanisms of catalysis lowers the energy of the reaction's transition state, by providing an alternative chemical pathway for the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Enzyme-substrate interactions align the reactive chemical groups and hold them close together in an optimal geometry, which increases the rate of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This reduces the entropy of the reactants and thus makes addition or transfer reactions less unfavorable, since a reduction in the overall entropy when two reactants become a single product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However this is a general effect and is seen in non-addition or transfer reactions where it occurs due to an increase in the "effective concentration" of the reagents.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This is understood when considering how increases in concentration leads to increases in reaction rate: essentially when the reactants are more concentrated, they collide more often and so react more often.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In enzyme catalysis, the binding of the reagents to the enzyme restricts the conformational space of the reactants, holding them in the 'proper orientation' and close to each other, so that they collide more frequently, of an with the correct geometry, to facilitate the desired reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The "effective concentration" is the concentration the reactant would have to be, free in solution, to experiences the same collisional frequency.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Often such theoretical effective concentrations are unphysical and impossible to realize in reality – which is a testament to the great catalytic power of many enzymes, with massive rate increases over the uncatalyzed state.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, the situation might be more complex, since modern computational studies have established that traditional examples of proximity effects cannot be related directly to enzyme entropic effects.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Also, the original entropic proposal has been found to largely overestimate the contribution of orientation entropy to catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Proton donors and acceptors, i.e. acids and base may donate and accept protons in order to stabilize developing charges in the transition state.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This is related to the overall principle of catalysis, that of reducing energy barriers, since in general transition states are high energy states, and by stabilizing them this high energy is reduced, lowering the barrier.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] A key feature of enzyme catalysis over many non-biological catalysis, is that both acid and base catalysis can be combined in the same reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In many abiotic systems, acids (large [H+]) or bases ( large concentration H+ sinks, or species with electron pairs) can increase the rate of the reaction; but of course the environment can only have one overall pH (measure of acidity or basicity (alkalinity)).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, since enzymes are large molecules, they can position both acid groups and basic groups in their active site to interact with their substrates, and employ both modes independent of the bulk pH.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Often general acid or base catalysis is employed to activate nucleophile and/or electrophile groups, or to stabilize leaving groups.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Many amino acids with acidic or basic groups are this employed in the active site, such as the glutamic and aspartic acid, histidine, cystine, tyrosine, lysine and arginine, as well as serine and threonine.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In addition, the peptide backbone, with carbonyl and amide N groups is often employed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Cystine and Histidine are very commonly involved, since they both have a pKa close to neutral pH and can therefore both accept and donate protons.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Many reaction mechanisms involving acid/base catalysis assume a substantially altered pKa.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This alteration of pKa is possible through the local environment of the residue.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] pKa can also be influenced significantly by the surrounding environment, to the extent that residues which are basic in solution may act as proton donors, and vice versa.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The modification of the pKa's is a pure part of the electrostatic mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The catalytic effect of the above example is mainly associated with the reduction of the pKa of the oxyanion and the increase in the pKa of the histidine, while the proton transfer from the serine to the histidine is not catalyzed significantly since it is not the rate determining barrier.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Note that in the example shown, the histidine conjugate acid acts as a general acid catalyst for the subsequent loss of the amine from a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Evidence supporting this proposed mechanism (Figure 4 in Ref.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Stabilization of charged transition states can also be by residues in the active site forming ionic bonds (or partial ionic charge interactions) with the intermediate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] These bonds can either come from acidic or basic side chains found on amino acids such as lysine, arginine, aspartic acid or glutamic acid or come from metal cofactors such as zinc.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Metal ions are particularly effective and can reduce the pKa of water enough to make it an effective nucleophile.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Systematic computer simulation studies have established that electrostatic effects give, by far, the largest contribution to catalysis, and can increase the rate of reaction by a factor of up to 107.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In particular, it has been found that enzymes provide an environment which is more polar than water, and that ionic transition states are stabilized by fixed dipoles.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This is very different from transition state stabilization in water, where the water molecules must pay with "reorganization energy" in order to stabilize ionic and charged states.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Thus, catalysis is associated with the fact that the enzyme polar groups are preorganized.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The magnitude of the electrostatic field exerted by an enzyme's active site has been shown to be highly correlated with the enzyme's catalytic rate enhancement.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Binding of substrate usually excludes water from the active site, thereby lowering the local dielectric constant to that of an organic solvent.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This strengthens the electrostatic interactions between the charged/polar substrates and the active sites.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In addition, studies have shown that the charge distributions about the active sites are arranged so as to stabilize the transition states of the catalyzed reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In several enzymes, these charge distributions apparently serve to guide polar substrates toward their binding sites so that the rates of these enzymatic reactions are greater than their apparent diffusion-controlled limits.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Describing the dielectric constant in the enzyme–substrate complex as a single, low macroscopic value represents a significant oversimplification.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In practice, the effective macroscopic dielectric constant of proteins can be relatively high (see, for example,).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] What is most relevant is that enzyme active sites are highly polar environments, in which polar groups are preorganized to stabilize the transition state.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Covalent catalysis involves the substrate forming a transient covalent bond with residues in the enzyme active site or with a cofactor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This adds an additional covalent intermediate to the reaction, and helps to reduce the energy of later transition states of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The covalent bond must, at a later stage in the reaction, be broken to regenerate the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This mechanism is utilised by the catalytic triad of enzymes such as proteases like chymotrypsin and trypsin, where an acyl-enzyme intermediate is formed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] An alternative mechanism is schiff base formation using the free amine from a lysine residue, as seen in the enzyme aldolase during glycolysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Some enzymes utilize non-amino acid cofactors such as pyridoxal phosphate (PLP) or thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP) to form covalent intermediates with reactant molecules.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes utilizing such cofactors include the PLP-dependent enzyme aspartate transaminase and the TPP-dependent enzyme pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Rather than lowering the activation energy for a reaction pathway, covalent catalysis provides an alternative pathway for the reaction (via to the covalent intermediate) and so is distinct from true catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] For example, the energetics of the covalent bond to the serine molecule in chymotrypsin should be compared to the well-understood covalent bond to the nucleophile in the uncatalyzed solution reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] A metal ion in the active site participates in catalysis by coordinating charge stabilization and shielding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Because of a metal's positive charge, only negative charges can be stabilized through metal ions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, metal ions are advantageous in biological catalysis because they are not affected by changes in pH.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Metal ions can also act to ionize water by acting as a Lewis acid.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Metal ions may also be agents of oxidation and reduction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This is the principal effect of induced fit binding, where the affinity of the enzyme to the transition state is greater than to the substrate itself.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This induces structural rearrangements which strain substrate bonds into a position closer to the conformation of the transition state, so lowering the energy difference between the substrate and transition state and helping catalyze the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, the strain effect is, in fact, a ground state destabilization effect, rather than transition state stabilization effect.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Furthermore, enzymes are very flexible and they cannot apply large strain effect.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In addition to bond strain in the substrate, bond strain may also be induced within the enzyme itself to activate residues in the active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] These traditional "over the barrier" mechanisms have been challenged in some cases by models and observations of "through the barrier" mechanisms (quantum tunneling).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Some enzymes operate with kinetics which are faster than what would be predicted by the classical ΔG‡.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In "through the barrier" models, a proton or an electron can tunnel through activation barriers.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Quantum tunneling for protons has been observed in tryptamine oxidation by aromatic amine dehydrogenase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Quantum tunneling does not appear to provide a major catalytic advantage, since the tunneling contributions are similar in the catalyzed and the uncatalyzed reactions in solution.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, the tunneling contribution (typically enhancing rate constants by a factor of ~1000 compared to the rate of reaction for the classical 'over the barrier' route) is likely crucial to the viability of biological organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This emphasizes the general importance of tunneling reactions in biology.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, as stated above, this does not represent a true catalytic effect, since the same enhancement exists in the corresponding reference reaction in solution.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] In 1971-1972 the first quantum-mechanical model of enzyme catalysis was formulated.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, this study did not include any representation of the enzyme environment, nor did it provide a relevant potential energy surface.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Consequently, it cannot be considered a true quantum mechanical study of enzyme catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Such investigations became feasible only with the development of combined quantum mechanical/molecular mechanical (QM/MM) methods.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The binding energy of the enzyme-substrate complex cannot be considered as an external energy which is necessary for the substrate activation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] It may be seen from reaction (**1**) that the group X1 of the active enzyme appears in the product due to possibility of the exchange reaction inside enzyme to avoid both electrostatic inhibition and repulsion of atoms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] So we represent the active enzyme as a powerful reactant of the enzymatic reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The reaction (**2**) shows incomplete conversion of the substrate because its group X2 remains inside enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This approach as idea had formerly proposed relying on the hypothetical extremely high enzymatic conversions (catalytically perfect enzyme).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The crucial point for the verification of the present approach is that the catalyst must be a complex of the enzyme with the transfer group of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This chemical aspect is supported by the well-studied mechanisms of the several enzymatic reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Consider the reaction of peptide bond hydrolysis catalyzed by a pure protein α-chymotrypsin (an enzyme acting without a cofactor), which is a well-studied member of the serine proteases family, see.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] where S1 is a polypeptide, P1 and P2 are products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The first chemical step (**3**) includes the formation of a covalent acyl-enzyme intermediate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The second step (**4**) is the deacylation step.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The group H+, initially found on the enzyme, but not in water, appears in the product before the step of hydrolysis, therefore it may be considered as an additional group of the enzymatic reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Thus, the reaction (**3**) shows that the enzyme acts as a powerful reactant of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] According to the proposed concept, the H transport from the enzyme promotes the first reactant conversion, breakdown of the first initial chemical bond (between groups P1 and P2).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The step of hydrolysis leads to a breakdown of the second chemical bond and regeneration of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The proposed chemical mechanism does not depend on the concentration of the substrates or products in the medium.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] However, a shift in their concentration mainly causes free energy changes in the first and final steps of the reactions (**1**) and (**2**) due to the changes in the free energy content of every molecule, whether S or P, in water solution.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This approach is in accordance with the following mechanism of muscle contraction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The final step of ATP hydrolysis in skeletal muscle is the product release caused by the association of myosin heads with actin.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The closing of the actin-binding cleft during the association reaction is structurally coupled with the opening of the nucleotide-binding pocket on the myosin active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Notably, the final steps of ATP hydrolysis include the fast release of phosphate and the slow release of ADP.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The release of a phosphate anion from bound ADP anion into water solution may be considered as an exergonic reaction because the phosphate anion has low molecular mass.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Thus, we arrive at the conclusion that the primary release of the inorganic phosphate H2PO4− leads to transformation of a significant part of the free energy of ATP hydrolysis into the kinetic energy of the solvated phosphate, producing active streaming.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] This assumption of a local mechano-chemical transduction is in accord with Tirosh's mechanism of muscle contraction, where the muscle force derives from an integrated action of active streaming created by ATP hydrolysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Triose phosphate isomerase (EC 5.3.1.1) catalyses the reversible interconversion of the two triose phosphates isomers dihydroxyacetone phosphate and D-glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Trypsin (EC 3.4.21.4) is a serine protease that cleaves protein substrates after lysine or arginine residues using a catalytic triad to perform covalent catalysis, and an oxyanion hole to stabilise charge-buildup on the transition states.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Aldolase (EC 4.1.2.13) catalyses the breakdown of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate (F-1,6-BP) into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] The advent of single-molecule studies in the 2010s led to the observation that the movement of untethered enzymes increases with increasing substrate concentration and increasing reaction enthalpy.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Subsequent observations suggest that this increase in diffusivity is driven by transient displacement of the enzyme's center of mass, resulting in a "recoil effect that propels the enzyme".
[src:enzymology/enzyme-catalysis] Similarity between enzymatic reactions (EC) can be calculated by using bond changes, reaction centres or substructure metrics (EC-BLAST Archived 30 May 2019 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An **enzyme inhibitor** is a molecule that binds to an enzyme and blocks its activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzymes are proteins that speed up chemical reactions necessary for life, in which substrate molecules are converted into products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme facilitates a specific chemical reaction by binding the substrate to its active site, a specialized area on the enzyme that accelerates the most difficult step of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme inhibitor stops ("inhibits") this process, either by binding to the enzyme's active site (thus preventing the substrate itself from binding) or by binding to another site on the enzyme such that the enzyme's catalysis of the reaction is blocked.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors may bind reversibly or irreversibly.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors form a chemical bond with the enzyme such that the enzyme is inhibited until the chemical bond is broken.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] By contrast, reversible inhibitors bind non-covalently and may spontaneously leave the enzyme, allowing the enzyme to resume its function.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors produce different types of inhibition depending on whether they bind to the enzyme, the enzyme-substrate complex, or both.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors play an important role in all cells, since they are generally specific to one enzyme each and serve to control that enzyme's activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, enzymes in a metabolic pathway may be inhibited by molecules produced later in the pathway, thus curtailing the production of molecules that are no longer needed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of negative feedback is an important way to maintain balance in a cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors also control essential enzymes such as proteases or nucleases that, if left unchecked, may damage a cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Many poisons produced by animals or plants are enzyme inhibitors that block the activity of crucial enzymes in prey or predators.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Many drug molecules are enzyme inhibitors that inhibit an aberrant human enzyme or an enzyme critical for the survival of a pathogen such as a virus, bacterium or parasite.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Examples include methotrexate (used in chemotherapy and in treating rheumatic arthritis) and the protease inhibitors used to treat HIV/AIDS.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Since anti-pathogen inhibitors generally target only one enzyme, such drugs are highly specific and generally produce few side effects in humans, provided that no analogous enzyme is found in humans.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] (This is often the case, since such pathogens and humans are genetically distant.) Medicinal enzyme inhibitors often have low dissociation constants, meaning that only a minute amount of the inhibitor is required to inhibit the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A low concentration of the enzyme inhibitor reduces the risk for liver and kidney damage and other adverse drug reactions in humans.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence the discovery and refinement of enzyme inhibitors is an active area of research in biochemistry and pharmacology.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are a chemically diverse set of substances that range in size from organic small molecules to macromolecular proteins.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Small molecule inhibitors include essential primary metabolites that inhibit upstream enzymes that produce those metabolites.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This provides a negative feedback loop that prevents over production of metabolites and thus maintains cellular homeostasis (steady internal conditions).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Small molecule enzyme inhibitors also include secondary metabolites, which are not essential to the organism that produces them, but provide the organism with an evolutionary advantage, in that they can be used to repel predators or competing organisms or immobilize prey.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition, many drugs are small molecule enzyme inhibitors that target either disease-modifying enzymes in the patient or enzymes in pathogens which are required for the growth and reproduction of the pathogen.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition to small molecules, some proteins act as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The most prominent example are serpins (**ser**ine **p**rotease **in**hibitors) which are produced by animals to protect against inappropriate enzyme activation and by plants to prevent predation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Another class of inhibitor proteins is the ribonuclease inhibitors, which bind to ribonucleases in one of the tightest known protein–protein interactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A special case of protein enzyme inhibitors are zymogens that contain an autoinhibitory N-terminal peptide that binds to the active site of enzyme that intramolecularly blocks its activity as a protective mechanism against uncontrolled catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The N‑terminal peptide is cleaved (split) from the zymogen enzyme precursor by another enzyme to release an active enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The binding site of inhibitors on enzymes is most commonly the same site that binds the substrate of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These active site inhibitors are known as orthosteric ("regular" orientation) inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The mechanism of orthosteric inhibition is simply to prevent substrate binding to the enzyme through direct competition which in turn prevents the enzyme from catalysing the conversion of substrates into products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Alternatively, the inhibitor can bind to a site remote from the enzyme active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These are known as allosteric ("alternative" orientation) inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Kinetic mechanisms for reversible inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate (S) binding to enzyme (E) in blue, catalysis releasing product (P) in red, inhibitor (I) binding to enzyme in green.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Binding site in blue, substrate in black, inhibitor in green, and allosteric site in light green.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Competitive inhibitors usually bind to the active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Non-competitive bind to a remote (allosteric) site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Uncompetitive inhibitors only bind once the substrate is bound, fully disrupting catalysis, and mixed inhibition is similar but with only partial disruption of catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors attach to enzymes with non-covalent interactions such as hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions and ionic bonds.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Multiple weak bonds between the inhibitor and the enzyme active site combine to produce strong and specific binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In contrast to irreversible inhibitors, reversible inhibitors generally do not undergo chemical reactions when bound to the enzyme and can be easily removed by dilution or dialysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A special case is **covalent reversible inhibitors** that form a chemical bond with the enzyme, but the bond can be cleaved so the inhibition is fully reversible.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors are generally categorized into four types, as introduced by Cleland in 1963.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] They are classified according to the effect of the inhibitor on the *Vmax* (maximum reaction rate catalysed by the enzyme) and *Km* (the concentration of substrate resulting in half maximal enzyme activity) as the concentration of the enzyme's substrate is varied.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In competitive inhibition the substrate and inhibitor cannot bind to the enzyme at the same time.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This usually results from the inhibitor having an affinity for the active site of an enzyme where the substrate also binds; the substrate and inhibitor *compete* for access to the enzyme's active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of inhibition can be overcome by sufficiently high concentrations of substrate (*Vmax* remains constant), i.e., by out-competing the inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the apparent *Km* will increase as it takes a higher concentration of the substrate to reach the *Km* point, or half the *Vmax*.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Competitive inhibitors are often similar in structure to the real substrate (see for example the "methotrexate versus folate" figure in the "Drugs" section).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In uncompetitive inhibition the inhibitor binds only to the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In non-competitive inhibition the binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme reduces its activity but does not affect the binding of substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of inhibitor binds with equal affinity to the free enzyme as to the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] It can be thought of as having the ability of competitive and uncompetitive inhibitors, but with no preference to either type.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] As a result, the extent of inhibition depends only on the concentration of the inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] *Vmax* will decrease due to the inability for the reaction to proceed as efficiently, but *Km* will remain the same as the actual binding of the substrate, by definition, will still function properly.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In mixed inhibition the inhibitor may bind to the enzyme whether or not the substrate has already bound.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence mixed inhibition is a combination of competitive and noncompetitive inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Furthermore, the affinity of the inhibitor for the free enzyme and the enzyme-substrate complex may differ.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] By increasing concentrations of substrate [S], this type of inhibition can be reduced (due to the competitive contribution), but not entirely overcome (due to the noncompetitive component).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Although it is possible for mixed-type inhibitors to bind in the active site, this type of inhibition generally results from an allosteric effect where the inhibitor binds to a different site on an enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitor binding to this allosteric site changes the conformation (that is, the tertiary structure or three-dimensional shape) of the enzyme so that the affinity of the substrate for the active site is reduced.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These four types of inhibition can also be distinguished by the effect of increasing the substrate concentration [S] on the degree of inhibition caused by a given amount of inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For competitive inhibition the degree of inhibition is reduced by increasing [S], for noncompetitive inhibition the degree of inhibition is unchanged, and for uncompetitive (also called anticompetitive) inhibition the degree of inhibition increases with [S].
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibition can be described quantitatively in terms of the inhibitor's binding to the enzyme and to the enzyme-substrate complex, and its effects on the kinetic constants of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In the classic Michaelis-Menten scheme (shown in the "inhibition mechanism schematic" diagram), an enzyme (E) binds to its substrate (S) to form the enzyme–substrate complex ES.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Upon catalysis, this complex breaks down to release product P and free enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The inhibitor (I) can bind to either E or ES with the dissociation constants *K*i or *K*i', respectively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] When an enzyme has multiple substrates, inhibitors can show different types of inhibition depending on which substrate is considered.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This results from the active site containing two different binding sites within the active site, one for each substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, an inhibitor might compete with substrate A for the first binding site, but be a non-competitive inhibitor with respect to substrate B in the second binding site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Traditionally reversible enzyme inhibitors have been classified as competitive, uncompetitive, or non-competitive, according to their effects on *K*m and *V*max.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These three types of inhibition result respectively from the inhibitor binding only to the enzyme E in the absence of substrate S, to the enzyme–substrate complex ES, or to both.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The division of these classes arises from a problem in their derivation and results in the need to use two different binding constants for one binding event.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] It is further assumed that binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme results in 100% inhibition and fails to consider the possibility of partial inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The common form of the inhibitory term also obscures the relationship between the inhibitor binding to the enzyme and its relationship to any other binding term be it the Michaelis–Menten equation or a dose response curve associated with ligand receptor binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This rearrangement demonstrates that similar to the Michaelis–Menten equation, the maximal rate of reaction depends on the proportion of the enzyme population interacting with its substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] the effect of the inhibitor is a result of the percent of the enzyme population interacting with inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The only problem with this equation in its present form is that it assumes absolute inhibition of the enzyme with inhibitor binding, when in fact there can be a wide range of effects anywhere from 100% inhibition of substrate turn over to no inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] To account for this the equation can be easily modified to allow for different degrees of inhibition by including a delta *V*max term.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This term can then define the residual enzymatic activity present when the inhibitor is interacting with individual enzymes in the population.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However the inclusion of this term has the added value of allowing for the possibility of activation if the secondary *V*max term turns out to be higher than the initial term.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] To account for the possibly of activation as well the notation can then be rewritten replacing the inhibitor "I" with a modifier term (stimulator or inhibitor) denoted here as "X".
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] While this terminology results in a simplified way of dealing with kinetic effects relating to the maximum velocity of the Michaelis–Menten equation, it highlights potential problems with the term used to describe effects relating to the *K*m.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The *K*m relating to the affinity of the enzyme for the substrate should in most cases relate to potential changes in the binding site of the enzyme which would directly result from enzyme inhibitor interactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme inhibitor is characterised by its dissociation constant *K*i, the concentration at which the inhibitor half occupies the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In non-competitive inhibition the inhibitor can also bind to the enzyme-substrate complex, and the presence of bound substrate can change the affinity of the inhibitor for the enzyme, resulting in a second dissociation constant *K*i'.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence *K*i and *K*i' are the dissociation constants of the inhibitor for the enzyme and to the enzyme-substrate complex, respectively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The enzyme-inhibitor constant *K*i can be measured directly by various methods; one especially accurate method is isothermal titration calorimetry, in which the inhibitor is titrated into a solution of enzyme and the heat released or absorbed is measured.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the other dissociation constant *K*i' is difficult to measure directly, since the enzyme-substrate complex is short-lived and undergoing a chemical reaction to form the product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence, *K*i' is usually measured indirectly, by observing the enzyme activity under various substrate and inhibitor concentrations, and fitting the data via nonlinear regression to a modified Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Thus, in the presence of the inhibitor, the enzyme's effective *K*m and *V*max become (α/α')*K*m and (1/α')*V*max, respectively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the modified Michaelis-Menten equation assumes that binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme has reached equilibrium, which may be a very slow process for inhibitors with sub-nanomolar dissociation constants.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In these cases the inhibition becomes effectively irreversible, hence it is more practical to treat such tight-binding inhibitors as irreversible (see below).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The effects of different types of reversible enzyme inhibitors on enzymatic activity can be visualised using graphical representations of the Michaelis–Menten equation, such as Lineweaver–Burk, Eadie-Hofstee or Hanes-Woolf plots.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An illustration is provided by the three Lineweaver–Burk plots depicted in the *Lineweaver–Burk diagrams* figure.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In the top diagram the competitive inhibition lines intersect on the *y*-axis, illustrating that such inhibitors do not affect *V*max.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In the bottom diagram the non-competitive inhibition lines intersect on the *x*-axis, showing these inhibitors do not affect *K*m.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, since it can be difficult to estimate *K*i and *K*i' accurately from such plots, it is advisable to estimate these constants using more reliable nonlinear regression methods.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The mechanism of partially competitive inhibition is similar to that of non-competitive, except that the EIS complex has catalytic activity, which may be lower or even higher (partially competitive activation) than that of the enzyme–substrate (ES) complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition typically displays a lower *V*max, but an unaffected *K*m value.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate or product inhibition is where either an enzymes substrate or product also act as an inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition may follow the competitive, uncompetitive or mixed patterns.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In substrate inhibition there is a progressive decrease in activity at high substrate concentrations, potentially from an enzyme having two competing substrate-binding sites.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] At low substrate, the high-affinity site is occupied and normal kinetics are followed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, at higher concentrations, the second inhibitory site becomes occupied, inhibiting the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Product inhibition (either the enzyme's own product, or a product to an enzyme downstream in its metabolic pathway) is often a regulatory feature in metabolism and can be a form of negative feedback.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Slow-tight inhibition occurs when the initial enzyme–inhibitor complex EI undergoes conformational isomerism (a change in shape) to a second more tightly held complex, EI*, but the overall inhibition process is reversible.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This manifests itself as slowly increasing enzyme inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Under these conditions, traditional Michaelis–Menten kinetics give a false value for *K*i, which is time–dependent.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The true value of *K*i can be obtained through more complex analysis of the on (*k*on) and off (*k*off) rate constants for inhibitor association with kinetics similar to irreversible inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] TGDDF/GDDF multi-substrate adduct inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate analogue in black, cofactor analogue in blue, non-cleavable linker in red.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Multi-substrate analogue inhibitors are high affinity selective inhibitors that can be prepared for enzymes that catalyse reactions with more than one substrate by capturing the binding energy of each of those substrate into one molecule.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Here the subnanomolar dissociation constant (KD) of TGDDF was greater than predicted presumably due to entropic advantages gained and/or positive interactions acquired through the atoms linking the components.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] MAIs have also been observed to be produced in cells by reactions of pro-drugs such as isoniazid or enzyme inhibitor ligands (for example, PTC124) with cellular cofactors such as nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) and adenosine triphosphate (ATP) respectively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] As enzymes have evolved to bind their substrates tightly, and most reversible inhibitors bind in the active site of enzymes, it is unsurprising that some of these inhibitors are strikingly similar in structure to the substrates of their targets.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitors of dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR) are prominent examples.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Other examples of these substrate mimics are the protease inhibitors, a therapeutically effective class of antiretroviral drugs used to treat HIV/AIDS.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The structure of ritonavir, a peptidomimetic (peptide mimic) protease inhibitor containing three peptide bonds, as shown in the "competitive inhibition" figure above.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] As this drug resembles the peptide that is the substrate of the HIV protease, it competes with the substrate in the enzyme's active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are often designed to mimic the transition state or intermediate of an enzyme-catalysed reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This ensures that the inhibitor exploits the transition state stabilising effect of the enzyme, resulting in a better binding affinity (lower *K*i) than substrate-based designs.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of such a transition state inhibitor is the antiviral drug oseltamivir; this drug mimics the planar nature of the ring oxonium ion in the reaction of the viral enzyme neuraminidase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, not all inhibitors are based on the structures of substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, the structure of another HIV protease inhibitor tipranavir is not based on a peptide and has no obvious structural similarity to a protein substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These non-peptide inhibitors can be more stable than inhibitors containing peptide bonds, because they will not be substrates for peptidases and are less likely to be degraded.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In drug design it is important to consider the concentrations of substrates to which the target enzymes are exposed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, some protein kinase inhibitors have chemical structures that are similar to ATP, one of the substrates of these enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, drugs that are simple competitive inhibitors will have to compete with the high concentrations of ATP in the cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Protein kinases can also be inhibited by competition at the binding sites where the kinases interact with their substrate proteins, and most proteins are present inside cells at concentrations much lower than the concentration of ATP.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] As a consequence, if two protein kinase inhibitors both bind in the active site with similar affinity, but only one has to compete with ATP, then the competitive inhibitor at the protein-binding site will inhibit the enzyme more effectively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors bind to the enzyme's binding site then undergo a chemical reaction to form a covalent enzyme-inhibitor complex (EI*).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Binding site in blue, inhibitor in green.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors covalently bind to an enzyme, and this type of inhibition can therefore not be readily reversed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors often contain reactive functional groups such as nitrogen mustards, aldehydes, haloalkanes, alkenes, Michael acceptors, phenyl sulfonates, or fluorophosphonates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These electrophilic groups react with amino acid side chains to form covalent adducts.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The residues modified are those with side chains containing nucleophiles such as hydroxyl or sulfhydryl groups; these include the amino acids serine (that reacts with DFP, see the "DFP reaction" diagram), and also cysteine, threonine, or tyrosine.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibition is different from irreversible enzyme inactivation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors are generally specific for one class of enzyme and do not inactivate all proteins; they do not function by destroying protein structure but by specifically altering the active site of their target.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, extremes of pH or temperature usually cause denaturation of all protein structure, but this is a non-specific effect.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Similarly, some non-specific chemical treatments destroy protein structure: for example, heating in concentrated hydrochloric acid will hydrolyse the peptide bonds holding proteins together, releasing free amino acids.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors display time-dependent inhibition and their potency therefore cannot be characterised by an IC50 value.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This is because the amount of active enzyme at a given concentration of irreversible inhibitor will be different depending on how long the inhibitor is pre-incubated with the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Instead, *k*obs/[*I*] values are used, where *k*obs is the observed pseudo-first order rate of inactivation (obtained by plotting the log of % activity versus time) and [*I*] is the concentration of inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The *k*obs/[*I*] parameter is valid as long as the inhibitor does not saturate binding with the enzyme (in which case *k*obs = *k*inact) where *k*inact is the rate of inactivation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Kinetic mechanism for irreversible inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate binding in blue, catalysis in red, inhibitor binding in green, inactivation reaction in dark green.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors first form a reversible non-covalent complex with the enzyme (EI or ESI).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Subsequently, a chemical reaction occurs between the enzyme and inhibitor to produce the covalently modified "dead-end complex" EI* (an irreversible covalent complex).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The rate at which EI* is formed is called the inactivation rate or *k*inact.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Since formation of EI may compete with ES, binding of irreversible inhibitors can be prevented by competition either with substrate or with a second, reversible inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This protection effect is good evidence of a specific reaction of the irreversible inhibitor with the active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The binding and inactivation steps of this reaction are investigated by incubating the enzyme with inhibitor and assaying the amount of activity remaining over time.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The activity will be decreased in a time-dependent manner, usually following exponential decay.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Fitting these data to a rate equation gives the rate of inactivation at this concentration of inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This is done at several different concentrations of inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] If a reversible EI complex is involved the inactivation rate will be saturable and fitting this curve will give *k*inact and *K*i.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Another method that is widely used in these analyses is mass spectrometry.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Here, accurate measurement of the mass of the unmodified native enzyme and the inactivated enzyme gives the increase in mass caused by reaction with the inhibitor and shows the stoichiometry of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This is usually done using a MALDI-TOF mass spectrometer.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In a complementary technique, peptide mass fingerprinting involves digestion of the native and modified protein with a protease such as trypsin.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This will produce a set of peptides that can be analysed using a mass spectrometer.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The peptide that changes in mass after reaction with the inhibitor will be the one that contains the site of modification.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Not all irreversible inhibitors form covalent adducts with their enzyme targets.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Some reversible inhibitors bind so tightly to their target enzyme that they are essentially irreversible.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These tight-binding inhibitors may show kinetics similar to covalent irreversible inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In these cases some of these inhibitors rapidly bind to the enzyme in a low-affinity EI complex and this then undergoes a slower rearrangement to a very tightly bound EI* complex (see the "irreversible inhibition mechanism" diagram).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This kinetic behaviour is called slow-binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This slow rearrangement after binding often involves a conformational change as the enzyme "clamps down" around the inhibitor molecule.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Examples of slow-binding inhibitors include some important drugs, such methotrexate, allopurinol, and the activated form of acyclovir.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Diisopropylfluorophosphate (DFP) is an example of an irreversible protease inhibitor (see the "DFP reaction" diagram).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The enzyme hydrolyses the phosphorus–fluorine bond, but the phosphate residue remains bound to the serine in the active site, deactivating it.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Similarly, DFP also reacts with the active site of acetylcholine esterase in the synapses of neurons, and consequently is a potent neurotoxin, with a lethal dose of less than 100 mg.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Suicide inhibition is an unusual type of irreversible inhibition where the enzyme converts the inhibitor into a reactive form in its active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An example is the inhibitor of polyamine biosynthesis, α-difluoromethylornithine (DFMO), which is an analogue of the amino acid ornithine, and is used to treat African trypanosomiasis (sleeping sickness).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Ornithine decarboxylase can catalyse the decarboxylation of DFMO instead of ornithine (see the "DFMO inhibitor mechanism" diagram).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, this decarboxylation reaction is followed by the elimination of a fluorine atom, which converts this catalytic intermediate into a conjugated imine, a highly electrophilic species.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This reactive form of DFMO then reacts with either a cysteine or lysine residue in the active site to irreversibly inactivate the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Since irreversible inhibition often involves the initial formation of a non-covalent enzyme inhibitor (EI) complex, it is sometimes possible for an inhibitor to bind to an enzyme in more than one way.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, in the figure showing trypanothione reductase from the human protozoan parasite *Trypanosoma cruzi*, two molecules of an inhibitor called *quinacrine mustard* are bound in its active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The top molecule is bound reversibly, but the lower one is bound covalently as it has reacted with an amino acid residue through its nitrogen mustard group.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are found in nature and also produced artificially in the laboratory.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Naturally occurring enzyme inhibitors regulate many metabolic processes and are essential for life.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition, naturally produced poisons are often enzyme inhibitors that have evolved for use as toxic agents against predators, prey, and competing organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] These natural toxins include some of the most poisonous substances known.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Artificial inhibitors are often used as drugs, but can also be insecticides such as malathion, herbicides such as glyphosate, or disinfectants such as triclosan.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Other artificial enzyme inhibitors block acetylcholinesterase, an enzyme which breaks down acetylcholine, and are used as nerve agents in chemical warfare.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibition is a common feature of metabolic pathway control in cells.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Metabolic flux through a pathway is often regulated by a pathway's metabolites acting as inhibitors and enhancers for the enzymes in that same pathway.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The glycolytic pathway is a classic example.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This catabolic pathway consumes glucose and produces ATP, NADH and pyruvate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A key step for the regulation of glycolysis is an early reaction in the pathway catalysed by phosphofructokinase‑1 (PFK1).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] When ATP levels rise, ATP binds an allosteric site in PFK1 to decrease the rate of the enzyme reaction; glycolysis is inhibited and ATP production falls.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This negative feedback control helps maintain a steady concentration of ATP in the cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] However, metabolic pathways are not just regulated through inhibition since enzyme activation is equally important.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] With respect to PFK1, fructose 2,6-bisphosphate and ADP are examples of metabolites that are allosteric activators.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Physiological enzyme inhibition can also be produced by specific protein inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This mechanism occurs in the pancreas, which synthesises many digestive precursor enzymes known as zymogens.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Many of these are activated by the trypsin protease, so it is important to inhibit the activity of trypsin in the pancreas to prevent the organ from digesting itself.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] One way in which the activity of trypsin is controlled is the production of a specific and potent trypsin inhibitor protein in the pancreas.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibitor binds tightly to trypsin, preventing the trypsin activity that would otherwise be detrimental to the organ.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Although the trypsin inhibitor is a protein, it avoids being hydrolysed as a substrate by the protease by excluding water from trypsin's active site and destabilising the transition state.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Other examples of physiological enzyme inhibitor proteins include the barstar inhibitor of the bacterial ribonuclease barnase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Animals and plants have evolved to synthesise a vast array of poisonous products including secondary metabolites, peptides and proteins that can act as inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Natural toxins are usually small organic molecules and are so diverse that there are probably natural inhibitors for most metabolic processes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The metabolic processes targeted by natural poisons encompass more than enzymes in metabolic pathways and can also include the inhibition of receptor, channel and structural protein functions in a cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, paclitaxel (taxol), an organic molecule found in the Pacific yew tree, binds tightly to tubulin dimers and inhibits their assembly into microtubules in the cytoskeleton.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Many natural poisons act as neurotoxins that can cause paralysis leading to death and function for defence against predators or in hunting and capturing prey.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Some of these natural inhibitors, despite their toxic attributes, are valuable for therapeutic uses at lower doses.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of a neurotoxin are the glycoalkaloids, from the plant species in the family Solanaceae (includes potato, tomato and eggplant), that are acetylcholinesterase inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibition of this enzyme causes an uncontrolled increase in the acetylcholine neurotransmitter, muscular paralysis and then death.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Neurotoxicity can also result from the inhibition of receptors; for example, atropine from deadly nightshade (*Atropa belladonna*) that functions as a competitive antagonist of the muscarinic acetylcholine receptors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Although many natural toxins are secondary metabolites, these poisons also include peptides and proteins.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of a toxic peptide is alpha-amanitin, which is found in relatives of the death cap mushroom.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This is a potent enzyme inhibitor, in this case preventing the RNA polymerase II enzyme from transcribing DNA.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The algal toxin microcystin is also a peptide and is an inhibitor of protein phosphatases.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This toxin can contaminate water supplies after algal blooms and is a known carcinogen that can also cause acute liver haemorrhage and death at higher doses.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Proteins can also be natural poisons or antinutrients, such as the trypsin inhibitors (discussed in the "metabolic regulation" section above) that are found in some legumes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A less common class of toxins are toxic enzymes: these act as irreversible inhibitors of their target enzymes and work by chemically modifying their substrate enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An example is ricin, an extremely potent protein toxin found in castor oil beans.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This enzyme is a glycosidase that inactivates ribosomes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Since ricin is a catalytic irreversible inhibitor, this allows just a single molecule of ricin to kill a cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The most common uses for enzyme inhibitors are as drugs to treat disease.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Many of these inhibitors target a human enzyme and aim to correct a pathological condition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For instance, aspirin is a widely used drug that acts as a suicide inhibitor of the cyclooxygenase enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition in turn suppresses the production of proinflammatory prostaglandins and thus aspirin may be used to reduce pain, fever, and inflammation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] As of 2017, an estimated 29% of approved drugs are enzyme inhibitors of which approximately one-fifth are kinase inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A notable class of kinase drug targets is the receptor tyrosine kinases which are essential enzymes that regulate cell growth; their over-activation may result in cancer.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence kinase inhibitors such as imatinib are frequently used to treat malignancies.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Janus kinases are another notable example of drug enzyme targets.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitors of Janus kinases block the production of inflammatory cytokines and hence these inhibitors are used to treat a variety of inflammatory diseases in including arthritis, asthma, and Crohn's disease.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of the structural similarity of some inhibitors to the substrates of the enzymes they target is seen in the figure comparing the drug methotrexate to folic acid.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Folic acid is the oxidised form of the substrate of dihydrofolate reductase, an enzyme that is potently inhibited by methotrexate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Methotrexate blocks the action of dihydrofolate reductase and thereby halts thymidine biosynthesis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This block of nucleotide biosynthesis is selectively toxic to rapidly growing cells, therefore methotrexate is often used in cancer chemotherapy.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A common treatment for erectile dysfunction is sildenafil (Viagra).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This compound is a potent inhibitor of cGMP specific phosphodiesterase type 5, the enzyme that degrades the signalling molecule cyclic guanosine monophosphate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This signalling molecule triggers smooth muscle relaxation and allows blood flow into the corpus cavernosum, which causes an erection.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Since the drug decreases the activity of the enzyme that halts the signal, it makes this signal last for a longer period of time.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Drugs are also used to inhibit enzymes needed for the survival of pathogens.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, bacteria are surrounded by a thick cell wall made of a net-like polymer called peptidoglycan.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Many antibiotics such as penicillin and vancomycin inhibit the enzymes that produce and then cross-link the strands of this polymer together.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This causes the cell wall to lose strength and the bacteria to burst.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] In the figure, a molecule of penicillin (shown in a ball-and-stick form) is shown bound to its target, the transpeptidase from the bacteria *Streptomyces* R61 (the protein is shown as a ribbon diagram).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Antibiotic drug design is facilitated when an enzyme that is essential to the pathogen's survival is absent or very different in humans.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Humans do not make peptidoglycan, therefore antibiotics that inhibit this process are selectively toxic to bacteria.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Selective toxicity is also produced in antibiotics by exploiting differences in the structure of the ribosomes in bacteria, or how they make fatty acids.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Drugs that inhibit enzymes needed for the replication of viruses are effective in treating viral infections.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Antiviral drugs include protease inhibitors used to treat HIV/AIDS and Hepatitis C, reverse-transcriptase inhibitors targeting HIV/AIDS, neuraminidase inhibitors targeting influenza, and terminase inhibitors targeting human cytomegalovirus.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Acetylcholinesterase (AChE) is an enzyme found in animals, from insects to humans.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] It is essential to nerve cell function through its mechanism of breaking down the neurotransmitter acetylcholine into its constituents, acetate and choline.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This is somewhat unusual among neurotransmitters as most, including serotonin, dopamine, and norepinephrine, are absorbed from the synaptic cleft rather than cleaved.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] A large number of AChE inhibitors are used in both medicine and agriculture.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible competitive inhibitors, such as edrophonium, physostigmine, and neostigmine, are used in the treatment of myasthenia gravis and in anaesthesia to reverse muscle blockade.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The carbamate pesticides are also examples of reversible AChE inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The organophosphate pesticides such as malathion, parathion, and chlorpyrifos irreversibly inhibit acetylcholinesterase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The herbicide glyphosate is an inhibitor of 3-phosphoshikimate 1-carboxyvinyltransferase, other herbicides, such as the sulfonylureas inhibit the enzyme acetolactate synthase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Both enzymes are needed for plants to make branched-chain amino acids.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Many other enzymes are inhibited by herbicides, including enzymes needed for the biosynthesis of lipids and carotenoids and the processes of photosynthesis and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] New drugs are the products of a long drug development process, the first step of which is often the discovery of a new enzyme inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] There are two principle approaches of discovering these inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The first general method is rational drug design based on mimicking the transition state of the chemical reaction catalysed by the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The designed inhibitor often closely resembles the substrate, except that the portion of the substrate that undergoes chemical reaction is replaced by a chemically stable functional group that resembles the transition state.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Since the enzyme has evolved to stabilise the transition state, transition state analogues generally possess higher affinity for the enzyme compared to the substrate, and therefore are effective inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] The second way of discovering new enzyme inhibitors is high-throughput screening of large libraries of structurally diverse compounds to identify hit molecules that bind to the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This method has been extended to include virtual screening of databases of diverse molecules using computers, which are then followed by experimental confirmation of binding of the virtual screening hits.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Complementary approaches that can provide new starting points for inhibitors include fragment-based lead discovery and DNA Encoded Chemical Libraries (DEL).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Hits from any of the above approaches can be optimised to high affinity binders that efficiently inhibit the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] Computer-based methods for predicting the binding orientation and affinity of an inhibitor for an enzyme such as molecular docking and molecular mechanics can be used to assist in the optimisation process.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] New inhibitors are used to obtain crystallographic structures of the enzyme in an inhibitor/enzyme complex to show how the molecule is binding to the active site, allowing changes to be made to the inhibitor to optimise binding in a process known as structure-based drug design.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-inhibitor] This test and improve cycle is repeated until a sufficiently potent inhibitor is produced.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] An enzyme, often written "E" in reactions, is a protein molecule that serves as a biological catalyst to facilitate and accelerate a chemical reaction in a cell or other biological environment.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] It does this through binding of one or more other molecules, its substrate (S), which the enzyme acts upon to form the desired product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The substrate binds to the active site of the enzyme to produce an enzyme-substrate complex (ES), and is transformed into an enzyme-product complex (EP) and from there to the product or products (P), via a transition state (ES*).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] When enzymes bind multiple substrates, such as dihydrofolate reductase, enzyme kinetics can also show the sequence in which these substrates bind and the sequence in which products are released.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] An example of enzymes that bind a single substrate and release multiple products are proteases, which cleave one protein substrate into two polypeptide products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Others join two substrates together, such as DNA polymerase linking a nucleotide to DNA.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Although these mechanisms are often a complex series of steps, there is typically one rate-determining step that determines the overall kinetics of the entire process.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This step may be a chemical reaction or a conformational change of the enzyme or substrates, such as those involved in the release of product(s) from the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Knowledge of the enzyme's structure is helpful in interpreting kinetic data.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] For example, the structure can suggest how substrates and products bind during catalysis; what changes occur during the reaction; and even the role of particular amino acid residues in the mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Some enzymes change shape significantly during the mechanism; in such cases, it is helpful to determine the enzyme structure with and without bound substrate analogues that do not undergo the enzymatic reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Not all biological catalysts are protein enzymes: RNA-based catalysts such as ribozymes and ribosomes are essential to many cellular functions, such as RNA splicing and translation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The main difference between ribozymes and enzymes is that RNA catalysts are composed of nucleotides, whereas enzymes are composed of amino acids.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Ribozymes also perform a more limited set of reactions, although their mechanisms and kinetics can be analysed and classified by the same methods.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The reaction catalysed by an enzyme uses exactly the same reactants and produces exactly the same products as the uncatalysed reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Like other catalysts, enzymes do not alter the position of equilibrium between substrates and products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, unlike uncatalysed chemical reactions, enzyme-catalysed reactions display saturation kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, at relatively high substrate concentrations, the reaction rate asymptotically approaches the theoretical maximum; the enzyme active sites are almost all occupied by substrates resulting in saturation, and the reaction rate is determined by the intrinsic turnover rate of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The substrate concentration midway between these two limiting cases is denoted by *K*M.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Thus, *K*M is the substrate concentration at which the reaction velocity is half of the maximum velocity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The two important properties of enzyme kinetics are how easily the enzyme can be saturated with a substrate, and the maximum rate it can achieve.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Knowing these properties suggests what an enzyme might do in the cell and can show how the enzyme will respond to changes in these conditions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzyme assays are laboratory procedures that measure the rate of enzyme reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Since enzymes are not consumed by the reactions they catalyse, enzyme assays usually follow changes in the concentration of either substrates or products to measure the rate of reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Spectrophotometric assays observe the change in the absorbance of light between products and reactants; radiometric assays involve the incorporation or release of radioactivity to measure the amount of product made over time.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Spectrophotometric assays are most convenient since they allow the rate of the reaction to be measured continuously.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Although radiometric assays require the removal and counting of samples (i.e., they are discontinuous assays), they are usually extremely sensitive and can measure very low levels of enzyme activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] An analogous approach is to use mass spectrometry to monitor the incorporation or release of stable isotopes as the substrate is converted into product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Occasionally, an assay fails and approaches are essential to resurrect a failed assay.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The most sensitive enzyme assays use lasers focused through a microscope to observe changes in single enzyme molecules as they catalyse their reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] These measurements either use changes in the fluorescence of cofactors during an enzyme's reaction mechanism, or of fluorescent dyes added onto specific sites of the protein to report movements that occur during catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] These studies provide a new view of the kinetics and dynamics of single enzymes, as opposed to traditional enzyme kinetics, which observes the average behaviour of populations of millions of enzyme molecules.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] An example progress curve for an enzyme assay is shown above.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The enzyme produces product at an initial rate that is approximately linear for a short period after the start of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] As the reaction proceeds and substrate is consumed, the rate continuously slows (so long as the substrate is not still at saturating levels).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] To measure the initial (and maximal) rate, enzyme assays are typically carried out while the reaction has progressed only a few percent towards total completion.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The length of the initial rate period depends on the assay conditions and can range from milliseconds to hours.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, equipment for rapidly mixing liquids allows fast kinetic measurements at initial rates of less than one second.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] These very rapid assays are essential for measuring pre-steady-state kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Most enzyme kinetics studies concentrate on this initial, approximately linear part of enzyme reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, it is also possible to measure the complete reaction curve and fit this data to a non-linear rate equation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This way of measuring enzyme reactions is called progress-curve analysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This approach is useful as an alternative to rapid kinetics when the initial rate is too fast to measure accurately.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The Standards for Reporting Enzymology Data guidelines provide minimum information required to comprehensively report kinetic and equilibrium data from investigations of enzyme activities including corresponding experimental conditions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The guidelines have been developed to report functional enzyme data with rigor and robustness.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzymes with single-substrate mechanisms include isomerases such as triosephosphateisomerase or bisphosphoglycerate mutase, intramolecular lyases such as adenylate cyclase, and the hammerhead ribozyme, an RNA lyase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, some enzymes that only have a single substrate do not fall into this category of mechanisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Catalase is an example of this, as the enzyme reacts with a first molecule of hydrogen peroxide substrate, becomes oxidised and is then reduced by a second molecule of substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Although a single substrate is involved, the existence of a modified enzyme intermediate means that the mechanism of catalase is actually a ping–pong mechanism, a type of mechanism that is discussed in the *Multi-substrate reactions* section below.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] As enzyme-catalysed reactions are saturable, their rate of catalysis does not show a linear response to increasing substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] If the initial rate of the reaction is measured over a range of substrate concentrations (denoted as [S]), the initial reaction rate ( $v_{0}$ ) increases as [S] increases.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, as [S] gets higher, the enzyme becomes saturated with substrate and the initial rate reaches *V*max, the enzyme's maximum rate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In the Michaelis–Menten kinetic model of a single-substrate reaction there is an initial bimolecular reaction between the enzyme E and substrate S to form the enzyme–substrate complex ES.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The rate of enzymatic reaction increases with the increase of the substrate concentration up to a certain level called Vmax; at Vmax, increase in substrate concentration does not cause any increase in reaction rate as there is no more enzyme (E) available for reacting with substrate (S).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Here, the rate of reaction becomes dependent on the ES complex and the reaction becomes a unimolecular reaction with an order of zero.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Though the enzymatic mechanism for the unimolecular reaction ${\ce {ES ->[k_{cat}] E + P}}$ can be quite complex, there is typically one rate-determining enzymatic step that allows this reaction to be modelled as a single catalytic step with an apparent unimolecular rate constant *k*cat.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] If the reaction path proceeds over one or several intermediates, *k*cat will be a function of several elementary rate constants, whereas in the simplest case of a single elementary reaction (e.g. no intermediates) it will be identical to the elementary unimolecular rate constant *k*2.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The apparent unimolecular rate constant *k*cat is also called turnover number, and denotes the maximum number of enzymatic reactions catalysed per second.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The Michaelis–Menten equation describes how the (initial) reaction rate *v*0 depends on the position of the substrate-binding equilibrium and the rate constant *k*2.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This Michaelis–Menten equation is the basis for most single-substrate enzyme kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Two crucial assumptions underlie this equation (apart from the general assumption about the mechanism only involving no intermediate or product inhibition, and there is no allostericity or cooperativity).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The Michaelis constant *K*M is experimentally defined as the concentration at which the rate of the enzyme reaction is half *V*max, which can be verified by substituting [S] = *K*M into the Michaelis–Menten equation and can also be seen graphically.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] If the rate-determining enzymatic step is slow compared to substrate dissociation ( $k_{2}\ll k_{-1}$ ), the Michaelis constant *K*M is roughly the dissociation constant *K*D of the ES complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Thus the product formation rate depends on the enzyme concentration as well as on the substrate concentration, the equation resembles a bimolecular reaction with a corresponding pseudo-second order rate constant $k_{2}/K_{M}$ .
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This constant is a measure of catalytic efficiency.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The most efficient enzymes reach a $k_{2}/K_{M}$ in the range of 108 – 1010 M−1 s−1.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] These enzymes are so efficient they effectively catalyse a reaction each time they encounter a substrate molecule and have thus reached an upper theoretical limit for efficiency (diffusion limit); and are sometimes referred to as kinetically perfect enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The observed velocities predicted by the Michaelis–Menten equation can be used to directly model the time course disappearance of substrate and the production of product through incorporation of the Michaelis–Menten equation into the equation for first order chemical kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This can only be achieved, however, if one recognises the problem associated with the use of Euler's number in the description of first order chemical kinetics. i.e.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] *e*−*k* is a split constant that introduces a systematic error into calculations and can be rewritten as a single constant which represents the remaining substrate after each time period.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In 1983 Stuart Beal (and also independently Santiago Schnell and Claudio Mendoza in 1997) derived a closed form solution for the time course kinetics analysis of the Michaelis-Menten mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] where W[ ] is again the Lambert-W function.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The plot of *v* versus [S] above is not linear; although initially linear at low [S], it bends over to saturate at high [S].
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Before the modern era of nonlinear curve-fitting on computers, this nonlinearity could make it difficult to estimate *K*M and *V*max accurately.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Therefore, several researchers developed linearisations of the Michaelis–Menten equation, such as the Lineweaver–Burk plot, the Eadie–Hofstee diagram and the Hanes–Woolf plot.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] All of these linear representations can be useful for visualising data, but none should be used to determine kinetic parameters, as computer software is readily available that allows for more accurate determination by nonlinear regression methods.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The Lineweaver–Burk plot or double reciprocal plot is a common way of illustrating kinetic data.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This is produced by taking the reciprocal of both sides of the Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This is a linear form of the Michaelis–Menten equation and produces a straight line with the equation *y* = m*x* + c with a *y*-intercept equivalent to 1/*V*max and an *x*-intercept of the graph representing −1/*K*M.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] No experimental values can be taken at negative 1/[S]; the lower limiting value 1/[S] = 0 (the *y*-intercept) corresponds to an infinite substrate concentration, where *1/v=1/Vmax* thus, the *x*-intercept is an extrapolation of the experimental data taken at positive concentrations.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] More generally, the Lineweaver–Burk plot skews the importance of measurements taken at low substrate concentrations and thus can yield inaccurate estimates of *V*max and *K*M.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] A more accurate linear plotting method is the Eadie–Hofstee plot.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In this case, *v* is plotted against *v*/[S].
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In the third common linear representation, the Hanes–Woolf plot, [S]/*v* is plotted against [S].
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In general, data normalisation can help diminish the amount of experimental work and can increase the reliability of the output, and is suitable for both graphical and numerical analysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The study of enzyme kinetics is important for two basic reasons.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Firstly, it helps explain how enzymes work, and secondly, it helps predict how enzymes behave in living organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The kinetic constants defined above, *K*M and *V*max, are critical to attempts to understand how enzymes work together to control metabolism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Making these predictions is not trivial, even for simple systems.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] For example, oxaloacetate is formed by malate dehydrogenase within the mitochondrion.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Oxaloacetate can then be consumed by citrate synthase, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase or aspartate aminotransferase, feeding into the citric acid cycle, gluconeogenesis or aspartic acid biosynthesis, respectively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Being able to predict how much oxaloacetate goes into which pathway requires knowledge of the concentration of oxaloacetate as well as the concentration and kinetics of each of these enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This aim of predicting the behaviour of metabolic pathways reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Alternatively, one useful simplification of the metabolic modelling problem is to ignore the underlying enzyme kinetics and only rely on information about the reaction network's stoichiometry, a technique called flux balance analysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] where a complex with the enzyme and an intermediate exists and the intermediate is converted into product in a second step.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] We see that for the limiting case $k_{3}\gg k_{2}$ , thus when the last step from ${\ce {EI -> E + P}}$ is much faster than the previous step, we get again the original equation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Mathematically we have then $K_{M}^{\prime }\approx K_{M}$ and $k_{cat}\approx k_{2}$ .
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Multi-substrate reactions follow complex rate equations that describe how the substrates bind and in what sequence.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The analysis of these reactions is much simpler if the concentration of substrate A is kept constant and substrate B varied.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Under these conditions, the enzyme behaves just like a single-substrate enzyme, and a plot of *v* by [S] gives apparent *K*M and *V*max constants for substrate B.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] If a set of these measurements is performed at different fixed concentrations of A, these data can be used to work out what the mechanism of the reaction is.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] For an enzyme that takes two substrates A and B and turns them into two products P and Q, there are two types of mechanism: ternary complex and substituted-enzyme mechanisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In these enzymes, both substrates bind to the enzyme at the same time to produce an EAB ternary complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The order of binding can either be random (in a random mechanism) or substrates have to bind in a particular sequence (in an ordered mechanism).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] When a set of *v* by [S] curves (fixed A, varying B) from an enzyme with a ternary-complex mechanism are plotted in a Lineweaver–Burk plot, the set of lines produced will intersect.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzymes with ternary-complex mechanisms include glutathione *S*-transferase, dihydrofolate reductase and DNA polymerase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Ping–pong mechanism for an enzyme reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Intermediates contain substrates A and B or products P and Q.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzymes with a substituted-enzyme mechanism can exist in two states, E and a chemically modified form of the enzyme E*; this modified enzyme is known as an intermediate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In such mechanisms, substrate A binds, changes the enzyme to E* by, for example, transferring a chemical group to the active site, and is then released.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Only after the first substrate is released can substrate B bind and react with the modified enzyme, regenerating the unmodified E form.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] When a set of *v* by [S] curves (fixed A, varying B) from an enzyme with a substituted-enzyme mechanism are plotted in a Lineweaver–Burk plot, a set of parallel lines will be produced.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzymes with substituted-enzyme mechanisms include some oxidoreductases such as thioredoxin peroxidase, transferases such as acylneuraminate cytidylyltransferase and serine proteases such as trypsin and chymotrypsin.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Serine proteases are a very common and diverse family of enzymes, including digestive enzymes (trypsin, chymotrypsin, and elastase), several enzymes of the blood clotting cascade, and many others.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In these serine proteases, the E* intermediate is an acyl-enzyme species formed by the attack of an active site serine residue on a peptide bond in a protein substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Both of these two types of mechanism can display enzyme memory, with very different causes and consequences in the two cases.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In ternary complex mechanisms, these are possible if the mechanism includes slow processes and the binding steps are not at quasi-equilibrium, because the intermediates may be swept away very fast.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This can generate cooperativity, even in monomeric enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In a substituted-enzyme mechanism, slow steps are not needed to generate memory effects.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Instead, for an enzyme with several alternative substrates, the kinetic properties of the second half reaction may vary with different substrates in the first half reaction, even though the same substituted enzyme seems to be transformed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] External factors may limit the ability of an enzyme to catalyse a reaction in both directions (whereas the nature of a catalyst in itself means that it cannot catalyse just one direction, according to the principle of microscopic reversibility).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] $v_{0}$ is positive if the reaction proceed in the forward direction ( $S\rightarrow P$ ) and negative otherwise.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This shows that thermodynamics forces a relation between the values of the four rate constants.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Their ratio is not equal to the equilibrium constant, which implies that thermodynamics does not constrain the ratio of the maximal rates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This explains that enzymes can be much "better catalysts" (*in terms of maximal rates*) in one particular direction of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Therefore, thermodynamics constrains the ratio between the forward and backward $V_{\rm {max}}/K_{M}$ values, not the ratio of $V_{\rm {max}}$ values.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Many different enzyme systems follow non-Michaelis-Menten behavior.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] A select few examples include kinetics of self-catalytic enzymes, cooperative and allosteric enzymes, interfacial and intracellular enzymes, processive enzymes, and so forth.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Some enzymes produce a sigmoid *v* by [S] plot, which often indicates cooperative binding of substrate to the active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This means that the binding of one substrate molecule affects the binding of subsequent substrate molecules.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This behavior is most common in multimeric enzymes with several interacting active sites.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Here, the mechanism of cooperation is similar to that of hemoglobin, with binding of substrate to one active site altering the affinity of the other active sites for substrate molecules.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Positive cooperativity occurs when binding of the first substrate molecule *increases* the affinity of the other active sites for substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Negative cooperativity occurs when binding of the first substrate *decreases* the affinity of the enzyme for other substrate molecules.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Allosteric enzymes include mammalian tyrosyl tRNA-synthetase, which shows negative cooperativity, and bacterial aspartate transcarbamoylase and phosphofructokinase which show positive cooperativity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Cooperativity is common and can help regulate the responses of enzymes to changes in the concentrations of their substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Positive cooperativity makes enzymes much more sensitive to [S] and their activities can show large changes over a narrow range of substrate concentration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Conversely, negative cooperativity makes enzymes insensitive to small changes in [S].
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The Hill equation is often used to describe the degree of cooperativity quantitatively in non-Michaelis–Menten kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The derived Hill coefficient *n* measures how much the binding of substrate to one active site affects the binding of substrate to the other active sites.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] A Hill coefficient of <1 indicates negative cooperativity and a coefficient of >1 indicates positive cooperativity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In the first moment after an enzyme is mixed with substrate, no product has been formed and no intermediates exist.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The study of the next few milliseconds of the reaction is called pre-steady-state kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Pre-steady-state kinetics is therefore concerned with the formation and consumption of enzyme–substrate intermediates (such as ES or E*) until their steady-state concentrations are reached.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This approach was first applied to the hydrolysis reaction catalysed by chymotrypsin.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Often, the detection of an intermediate is a vital piece of evidence in investigations of what mechanism an enzyme follows.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] For example, in the ping–pong mechanisms that are shown above, rapid kinetic measurements can follow the release of product P and measure the formation of the modified enzyme intermediate E*.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In the case of chymotrypsin, this intermediate is formed by an attack on the substrate by the nucleophilic serine in the active site and the formation of the acyl-enzyme intermediate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In the figure, the enzyme produces E* rapidly in the first few seconds of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The rate then slows as steady state is reached.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This rapid burst phase of the reaction measures a single turnover of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Consequently, the amount of product released in this burst, shown as the intercept on the *y*-axis of the graph, also gives the amount of functional enzyme which is present in the assay.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] An important goal of measuring enzyme kinetics is to determine the chemical mechanism of an enzyme reaction, i.e., the sequence of chemical steps that transform substrate into product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The kinetic approaches discussed above will show at what rates intermediates are formed and inter-converted, but they cannot identify exactly what these intermediates are.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Kinetic measurements taken under various solution conditions or on slightly modified enzymes or substrates often shed light on this chemical mechanism, as they reveal the rate-determining step or intermediates in the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] For example, the breaking of a covalent bond to a hydrogen atom is a common rate-determining step.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Which of the possible hydrogen transfers is rate determining can be shown by measuring the kinetic effects of substituting each hydrogen by deuterium, its stable isotope.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The rate will change when the critical hydrogen is replaced, due to a primary kinetic isotope effect, which occurs because bonds to deuterium are harder to break than bonds to hydrogen.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] It is also possible to measure similar effects with other isotope substitutions, such as 13C/12C and 18O/16O, but these effects are more subtle.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Isotopes can also be used to reveal the fate of various parts of the substrate molecules in the final products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] For example, it is sometimes difficult to discern the origin of an oxygen atom in the final product, since it may have come from water or from part of the substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This may be determined by systematically substituting oxygen's stable isotope 18O into the various molecules that participate in the reaction and checking for the isotope in the product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzyme inhibitors are molecules that reduce or abolish enzyme activity, while enzyme activators are molecules that increase the catalytic rate of enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] These interactions can be either *reversible* (i.e., removal of the inhibitor restores enzyme activity) or *irreversible* (i.e., the inhibitor permanently inactivates the enzyme).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Traditionally, reversible enzyme inhibitors have been classified as competitive, uncompetitive, or non-competitive, according to their effects on *K*M and *V*max.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] These different effects result from the inhibitor binding to the enzyme E, to the enzyme–substrate complex ES, or to both, respectively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The binding of an inhibitor and its effect on the enzymatic activity are two distinctly different things, another problem the traditional equations fail to acknowledge.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In noncompetitive inhibition the binding of the inhibitor results in 100% inhibition of the enzyme only, and fails to consider the possibility of anything in between.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In noncompetitive inhibition, the inhibitor will bind to an enzyme at its allosteric site; therefore, the binding affinity, or inverse of *K*M, of the substrate with the enzyme will remain the same.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] On the other hand, the Vmax will decrease relative to an uninhibited enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, the presence of a noncompetitive inhibitor is illustrated by a change in the y-intercept, defined as 1/Vmax.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The x-intercept, defined as −1/*K*M, will remain the same.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In competitive inhibition, the inhibitor will bind to an enzyme at the active site, competing with the substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] As a result, the *K*M will increase and the Vmax will remain the same.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The common form of the inhibitory term also obscures the relationship between the inhibitor binding to the enzyme and its relationship to any other binding term, be it the Michaelis–Menten equation or a dose response curve associated with ligand receptor binding.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This notation demonstrates that similar to the Michaelis–Menten equation, where the rate of reaction depends on the percent of the enzyme population interacting with substrate, the effect of the inhibitor is a result of the percent of the enzyme population interacting with inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The only problem with this equation in its present form is that it assumes absolute inhibition of the enzyme with inhibitor binding, when in fact there can be a wide range of effects anywhere from 100% inhibition of substrate turn over to just >0%.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] To account for this, the equation can be modified to allow for different degrees of inhibition by including a delta *V*max term.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, the inclusion of this term has the added value of allowing for the possibility of activation if the secondary *V*max term turns out to be higher than the initial term.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] To account for the possibly of activation as well, the notation can then be rewritten replacing the inhibitor "I" with a modifier term denoted here as "X".
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzyme inhibitors can also irreversibly inactivate enzymes, usually by covalently modifying active site residues.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] These reactions, which may be called suicide substrates, follow exponential decay functions and are usually saturable.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Below saturation, they follow first order kinetics with respect to inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Irreversible inhibition could be classified into two distinct types.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Affinity labelling is a type of irreversible inhibition where a functional group that is highly reactive modifies a catalytically critical residue on the protein of interest to bring about inhibition.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Mechanism-based inhibition, on the other hand, involves binding of the inhibitor followed by enzyme mediated alterations that transform the latter into a reactive group that irreversibly modifies the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The favoured model for the enzyme–substrate interaction is the induced fit model.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Conformational changes can be measured using circular dichroism or dual polarisation interferometry.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] After binding takes place, one or more mechanisms of catalysis lower the energy of the reaction's transition state by providing an alternative chemical pathway for the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Mechanisms of catalysis include catalysis by bond strain; by proximity and orientation; by active-site proton donors or acceptors; covalent catalysis and quantum tunnelling.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzymes can accelerate hydrogen transfer reactions by quantum tunneling, a phenomenon where particles such protons or electrons pass through an energy barrier rather than over it, due to their wave-like nature.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Enzyme kinetics cannot prove which modes of catalysis are used by an enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] However, some kinetic data can suggest possibilities to be examined by other techniques.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] For example, a ping–pong mechanism with burst-phase pre-steady-state kinetics would suggest covalent catalysis might be important in this enzyme's mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Alternatively, the observation of a strong pH effect on *V*max but not *K*M might indicate that a residue in the active site needs to be in a particular ionisation state for catalysis to occur.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In 1902 Victor Henri proposed a quantitative theory of enzyme kinetics, but at the time the experimental significance of the hydrogen ion concentration was not yet recognized.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] After Peter Lauritz Sørensen had defined the logarithmic pH-scale and introduced the concept of buffering in 1909, the German chemist Leonor Michaelis and Dr.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Maud Leonora Menten (a postdoctoral researcher in Michaelis's lab at the time) repeated Henri's experiments and confirmed his equation, which is now generally referred to as Michaelis-Menten kinetics (sometimes also *Henri-Michaelis-Menten kinetics*).
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] Haldane, who derived kinetic equations that are still widely considered today a starting point in modeling enzymatic activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The major contribution of the Henri-Michaelis-Menten approach was to think of enzyme reactions in two stages.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] In the first, the substrate binds reversibly to the enzyme, forming the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This is sometimes called the Michaelis complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The enzyme then catalyzes the chemical step in the reaction and releases the product.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] The kinetics of many enzymes is adequately described by the simple Michaelis-Menten model, but all enzymes have internal motions that are not accounted for in the model and can have significant contributions to the overall reaction kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme-kinetics] This can be modeled by introducing several Michaelis-Menten pathways that are connected with fluctuating rates, which is a mathematical extension of the basic Michaelis Menten mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An **enzyme** is a biological macromolecule, usually a protein, that acts as a biological catalyst, accelerating chemical reactions without being consumed in the process.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The molecules on which enzymes act are called substrates, which are converted into products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Nearly all metabolic processes within a cell depend on enzyme catalysis to occur at biologically relevant rates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A metabolic pathway is typically composed of a series of enzyme-catalyzed steps.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The study of enzymes is known as *enzymology*, and a related field focuses on pseudoenzymes—proteins that have lost catalytic activity but may retain regulatory or scaffolding functions, often indicated by alterations in their amino acid sequences or unusual 'pseudocatalytic' behavior.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes are known to catalyze over 5,000 types of biochemical reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Other biological catalysts include catalytic RNA molecules, or ribozymes, which are sometimes classified as enzymes despite being composed of RNA rather than protein.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] More recently, biomolecular condensates have been recognized as a third category of biocatalysts, capable of catalyzing reactions by creating interfaces and gradients—such as ionic gradients—that drive biochemical processes, even when their component proteins are not intrinsically catalytic.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes increase the reaction rate by lowering a reaction's activation energy, often by factors of millions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A striking example is orotidine 5′-phosphate decarboxylase, which accelerates a reaction that would otherwise take millions of years to occur in milliseconds.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Like all catalysts, enzymes do not affect the overall equilibrium of a reaction and are regenerated at the end of each cycle.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] What distinguishes them is their high specificity, determined by their unique three-dimensional structure, and their sensitivity to factors such as temperature and pH.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme activity can be enhanced by activators or diminished by inhibitors, many of which serve as drugs or poisons.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Outside optimal conditions, enzymes may lose their structure through denaturation, leading to loss of function.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes have widespread practical applications.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In industry, they are used to catalyze the production of antibiotics and other complex molecules.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In everyday life, enzymes in biological washing powders break down protein, starch, and fat stains, enhancing cleaning performance.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Papain and other proteolytic enzymes are used in meat tenderizers to hydrolyze proteins, improving texture and digestibility.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Their specificity and efficiency make enzymes indispensable in both biological systems and commercial processes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] By the late 17th and early 18th centuries, the digestion of meat by stomach secretions and the conversion of starch to sugars by plant extracts and saliva were known but the mechanisms by which these occurred had not been identified.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] French chemist Anselme Payen was the first to discover an enzyme, diastase, in 1833.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A few decades later, when studying the fermentation of sugar to alcohol by yeast, Louis Pasteur concluded that this fermentation was caused by a vital force contained within the yeast cells called "ferments", which were thought to function only within living organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In 1877, German physiologist Wilhelm Kühne (1837–1900) first used the term *enzyme*, which comes from Ancient Greek ἔνζυμον*(énzymon)* 'leavened, in yeast', to describe this process.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The word *enzyme* was used later to refer to nonliving substances such as pepsin, and the word *ferment* was used to refer to chemical activity produced by living organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Eduard Buchner submitted his first paper on the study of yeast extracts in 1897.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In a series of experiments at the University of Berlin, he found that sugar was fermented by yeast extracts even when there were no living yeast cells in the mixture.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] He named the enzyme that brought about the fermentation of sucrose "zymase".
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In 1907, he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for "his discovery of cell-free fermentation".
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Following Buchner's example, enzymes are usually named according to the reaction they carry out: the suffix *-ase* is combined with the name of the substrate (e.g., lactase is the enzyme that cleaves lactose) or to the type of reaction (e.g., DNA polymerase forms DNA polymers).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The biochemical identity of enzymes was still unknown in the early 1900s.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Many scientists observed that enzymatic activity was associated with proteins, but others (such as Nobel laureate Richard Willstätter) argued that proteins were merely carriers for the true enzymes and that proteins *per se* were incapable of catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Sumner showed that the enzyme urease was a pure protein and crystallized it; he did likewise for the enzyme catalase in 1937.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The conclusion that pure proteins can be enzymes was definitively demonstrated by John Howard Northrop and Wendell Meredith Stanley, who worked on the digestive enzymes pepsin (1930), trypsin and chymotrypsin.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These three scientists were awarded the 1946 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The discovery that enzymes could be crystallized eventually allowed their structures to be solved by x-ray crystallography.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This was first done for lysozyme, an enzyme found in tears, saliva and egg whites that digests the coating of some bacteria; the structure was solved by a group led by David Chilton Phillips and published in 1965.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This high-resolution structure of lysozyme marked the beginning of the field of structural biology and the effort to understand how enzymes work at an atomic level of detail.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes can be classified by two main criteria: either their enzymatic activity or their amino acid sequence similarity (and thus evolutionary relationship).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An enzyme's name is often derived from its substrate or the chemical reaction it catalyzes, with the word ending in *-ase*.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Examples are lactase, alcohol dehydrogenase and DNA polymerase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Different enzymes that catalyze the same chemical reaction are called isozymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology have developed a nomenclature for enzymes, the EC numbers (for "Enzyme Commission").
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Each enzyme is described by "EC" followed by a sequence of four numbers which represent the hierarchy of enzymatic activity (from very general to very specific).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] That is, the first number broadly classifies the enzyme based on its mechanism while the other digits add more and more specificity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These sections are subdivided by other features such as the substrate, products, and chemical mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An enzyme is fully specified by four numerical designations.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, hexokinase (EC 2.7.1.1) is a transferase (EC 2) that adds a phosphate group (EC 2.7) to a hexose sugar, a molecule containing an alcohol group (EC 2.7.1).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] EC categories do not reflect sequence similarity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For instance, two ligases of the same EC number that catalyze exactly the same reaction can have completely different sequences.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Independent of their function, enzymes, like any other proteins, have been classified by their sequence similarity into numerous families.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These families have been documented in dozens of different protein and protein family databases such as Pfam.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Unrelated enzymes that have the same enzymatic activity have been called *non-homologous isofunctional enzymes*.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Horizontal gene transfer may spread these genes to unrelated species, especially bacteria where they can replace endogenous genes of the same function, leading to hon-homologous gene displacement.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes are generally globular proteins, acting alone or in larger complexes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The sequence of the amino acids specifies the structure which in turn determines the catalytic activity of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Although structure determines function, a novel enzymatic activity cannot yet be predicted from structure alone.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme structures unfold (denature) when heated or exposed to chemical denaturants and this disruption to the structure typically causes a loss of activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes are usually much larger than their substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Sizes range from just 62 amino acid residues, for the monomer of 4-oxalocrotonate tautomerase, to over 2,500 residues in the animal fatty acid synthase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Only a small portion of their structure (around 2–4 amino acids) is directly involved in catalysis: the catalytic site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This catalytic site is located next to one or more binding sites where residues orient the substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The catalytic site and binding site together compose the enzyme's active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The remaining majority of the enzyme structure serves to maintain the precise orientation and dynamics of the active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In some enzymes, no amino acids are directly involved in catalysis; instead, the enzyme contains sites to bind and orient catalytic cofactors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme structures may also contain allosteric sites where the binding of a small molecule causes a conformational change that increases or decreases activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A small number of RNA-based biological catalysts called ribozymes exist, which again can act alone or in complex with proteins.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The most common of these is the ribosome which is a complex of protein and catalytic RNA components.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes must bind their substrates before they can catalyze any chemical reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes are usually very specific as to what substrates they bind and then the chemical reaction catalyzed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Specificity is achieved by binding pockets with complementary shape, charge and hydrophilic/hydrophobic characteristics to the substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes can therefore distinguish between very similar substrate molecules to be chemoselective, regioselective and stereospecific.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Some of the enzymes showing the highest specificity and accuracy are involved in the copying and expression of the genome.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Some of these enzymes have "proof-reading" mechanisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Here, an enzyme such as DNA polymerase catalyzes a reaction in a first step and then checks that the product is correct in a second step.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This two-step process results in average error rates of less than 1 error in 100 million reactions in high-fidelity mammalian polymerases.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Similar proofreading mechanisms are also found in RNA polymerase, aminoacyl tRNA synthetases and ribosomes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Conversely, some enzymes display enzyme promiscuity, having broad specificity and acting on a range of different physiologically relevant substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Many enzymes possess small side activities which arose fortuitously (i.e. neutrally), which may be the starting point for the evolutionary selection of a new function.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] To explain the observed specificity of enzymes, in 1894 Emil Fischer proposed that both the enzyme and the substrate possess specific complementary geometric shapes that fit exactly into one another.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This is often referred to as "the lock and key" model.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This early model explains enzyme specificity, but fails to explain the stabilization of the transition state that enzymes achieve.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In 1958, Daniel Koshland suggested a modification to the lock and key model: since enzymes are rather flexible structures, the active site is continuously reshaped by interactions with the substrate as the substrate interacts with the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] As a result, the substrate does not simply bind to a rigid active site; the amino acid side-chains that make up the active site are molded into the precise positions that enable the enzyme to perform its catalytic function.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In some cases, such as glycosidases, the substrate molecule also changes shape slightly as it enters the active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The active site continues to change until the substrate is completely bound, at which point the final shape and charge distribution is determined.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Induced fit may enhance the fidelity of molecular recognition in the presence of competition and noise via the conformational proofreading mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes may use several of these mechanisms simultaneously.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, proteases such as trypsin perform covalent catalysis using a catalytic triad, stabilize charge build-up on the transition states using an oxyanion hole, complete hydrolysis using an oriented water substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes are not rigid, static structures; instead they have complex internal dynamic motions – that is, movements of parts of the enzyme's structure such as individual amino acid residues, groups of residues forming a protein loop or unit of secondary structure, or even an entire protein domain.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These motions give rise to a conformational ensemble of slightly different structures that interconvert with one another at equilibrium.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Different states within this ensemble may be associated with different aspects of an enzyme's function.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, different conformations of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase are associated with the substrate binding, catalysis, cofactor release, and product release steps of the catalytic cycle, consistent with catalytic resonance theory.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The transitions between the different conformations during the catalytic cycle involve internal viscoelastic motion that is facilitated by high-strain regions where amino acids are rearranged.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Substrate presentation is a process where the enzyme is sequestered away from its substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes can be sequestered to the plasma membrane away from a substrate in the nucleus or cytosol.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Or within the membrane, an enzyme can be sequestered into lipid rafts away from its substrate in the disordered region.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] When the enzyme is released it mixes with its substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Alternatively, the enzyme can be sequestered near its substrate to activate the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, the enzyme can be soluble and upon activation bind to a lipid in the plasma membrane and then act upon molecules in the plasma membrane.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Allosteric sites are pockets on the enzyme, distinct from the active site, that bind to molecules in the cellular environment.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These molecules then cause a change in the conformation or dynamics of the enzyme that is transduced to the active site and thus affects the reaction rate of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In this way, allosteric interactions can either inhibit or activate enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Allosteric interactions with metabolites upstream or downstream in an enzyme's metabolic pathway cause feedback regulation, altering the activity of the enzyme according to the flux through the rest of the pathway.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Some enzymes do not need additional components to show full activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Others require non-protein molecules called cofactors to be bound for activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Cofactors can be either inorganic (e.g., metal ions and iron–sulfur clusters) or organic compounds (e.g., flavin and heme).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These cofactors serve many purposes; for instance, metal ions can help in stabilizing nucleophilic species within the active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Organic cofactors can be either coenzymes, which are released from the enzyme's active site during the reaction, or prosthetic groups, which are tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Organic prosthetic groups can be covalently bound (e.g., biotin in enzymes such as pyruvate carboxylase).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An example of an enzyme that contains a cofactor is carbonic anhydrase, which uses a zinc cofactor bound as part of its active site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These tightly bound ions or molecules are usually found in the active site and are involved in catalysis.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, flavin and heme cofactors are often involved in redox reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes that require a cofactor but do not have one bound are called *apoenzymes* or *apoproteins*.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An enzyme together with the cofactor(s) required for activity is called a *holoenzyme* (or haloenzyme).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The term *holoenzyme* can also be applied to enzymes that contain multiple protein subunits, such as the DNA polymerases; here the holoenzyme is the complete complex containing all the subunits needed for activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Coenzymes are small organic molecules that can be loosely or tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Coenzymes transport chemical groups from one enzyme to another.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Examples include NADH, NADPH and adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Some coenzymes, such as flavin mononucleotide (FMN), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), and tetrahydrofolate (THF), are derived from vitamins.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These coenzymes cannot be synthesized by the body *de novo* and closely related compounds (vitamins) must be acquired from the diet.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Since coenzymes are chemically changed as a consequence of enzyme action, it is useful to consider coenzymes to be a special class of substrates, or second substrates, which are common to many different enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, about 1000 enzymes are known to use the coenzyme NADH.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Coenzymes are usually continuously regenerated and their concentrations maintained at a steady level inside the cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, NADPH is regenerated through the pentose phosphate pathway and *S*-adenosylmethionine by methionine adenosyltransferase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This continuous regeneration means that small amounts of coenzymes can be used very intensively.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, the human body turns over its own weight in ATP each day.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] As with all catalysts, enzymes do not alter the position of the chemical equilibrium of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In the presence of an enzyme, the reaction runs in the same direction as it would without the enzyme, just more quickly.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The rate of a reaction is dependent on the activation energy needed to form the transition state which then decays into products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes increase reaction rates by lowering the energy of the transition state.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] First, binding forms a low energy enzyme-substrate complex (ES).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Second, the enzyme stabilises the transition state such that it requires less energy to achieve compared to the uncatalyzed reaction (ES‡).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Finally the enzyme-product complex (EP) dissociates to release the products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes can couple two or more reactions, so that a thermodynamically favorable reaction can be used to "drive" a thermodynamically unfavourable one so that the combined energy of the products is lower than the substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, the hydrolysis of ATP is often used to drive other chemical reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] for an enzyme reaction showing the relation between the substrate concentration and reaction rate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme kinetics is the investigation of how enzymes bind substrates and turn them into products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The rate data used in kinetic analyses are commonly obtained from enzyme assays.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In 1913 Leonor Michaelis and Maud Leonora Menten proposed a quantitative theory of enzyme kinetics, which is referred to as Michaelis–Menten kinetics.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The major contribution of Michaelis and Menten was to think of enzyme reactions in two stages.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This is sometimes called the Michaelis–Menten complex in their honor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Haldane, who derived kinetic equations that are still widely used today.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme rates depend on solution conditions and substrate concentration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] To find the maximum speed of an enzymatic reaction, the substrate concentration is increased until a constant rate of product formation is seen.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This is shown in the saturation curve on the right.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Saturation happens because, as substrate concentration increases, more and more of the free enzyme is converted into the substrate-bound ES complex.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] At the maximum reaction rate (*V*max) of the enzyme, all the enzyme active sites are bound to substrate, and the amount of ES complex is the same as the total amount of enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The efficiency of an enzyme can be expressed in terms of *k*cat/*K*m.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This is also called the specificity constant and incorporates the rate constants for all steps in the reaction up to and including the first irreversible step.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Because the specificity constant reflects both affinity and catalytic ability, it is useful for comparing different enzymes against each other, or the same enzyme with different substrates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The theoretical maximum for the specificity constant is called the diffusion limit and is about 108 to 109 (M−1 s−1).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] At this point every collision of the enzyme with its substrate will result in catalysis, and the rate of product formation is not limited by the reaction rate but by the diffusion rate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes with this property are called *catalytically perfect* or *kinetically perfect*.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Example of such enzymes are triose-phosphate isomerase, carbonic anhydrase, acetylcholinesterase, catalase, fumarase, β-lactamase, and superoxide dismutase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The turnover of such enzymes can reach several million reactions per second.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Michaelis–Menten kinetics relies on the law of mass action, which is derived from the assumptions of free diffusion and thermodynamically driven random collision.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Many biochemical or cellular processes deviate significantly from these conditions, because of macromolecular crowding and constrained molecular movement.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] More recent, complex extensions of the model attempt to correct for these effects.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] (right) are very similar in structure (differences show in green).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] As a result, methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of many enzymes that use folates.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme reaction rates can be decreased by various types of enzyme inhibitors.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A competitive inhibitor and substrate cannot bind to the enzyme at the same time.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Often competitive inhibitors strongly resemble the real substrate of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, the drug methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase, which catalyzes the reduction of dihydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The similarity between the structures of dihydrofolate and this drug are shown in the accompanying figure.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This type of inhibition can be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In some cases, the inhibitor can bind to a site other than the binding-site of the usual substrate and exert an allosteric effect to change the shape of the usual binding-site.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A non-competitive inhibitor binds to a site other than where the substrate binds.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The substrate still binds with its usual affinity and hence Km remains the same.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] However the inhibitor reduces the catalytic efficiency of the enzyme so that Vmax is reduced.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In contrast to competitive inhibition, non-competitive inhibition cannot be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An uncompetitive inhibitor cannot bind to the free enzyme, only to the enzyme-substrate complex; hence, these types of inhibitors are most effective at high substrate concentration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In the presence of the inhibitor, the enzyme-substrate complex is inactive.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A mixed inhibitor binds to an allosteric site and the binding of the substrate and the inhibitor affect each other.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The enzyme's function is reduced but not eliminated when bound to the inhibitor.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This type of inhibitor does not follow the Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An irreversible inhibitor permanently inactivates the enzyme, usually by forming a covalent bond to the protein.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Penicillin and aspirin are common drugs that act in this manner.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In many organisms, inhibitors may act as part of a feedback mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] If an enzyme produces too much of one substance in the organism, that substance may act as an inhibitor for the enzyme at the beginning of the pathway that produces it, causing production of the substance to slow down or stop when there is sufficient amount.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Major metabolic pathways such as the citric acid cycle make use of this mechanism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Since inhibitors modulate the function of enzymes they are often used as drugs.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Many such drugs are reversible competitive inhibitors that resemble the enzyme's native substrate, similar to methotrexate above; other well-known examples include statins used to treat high cholesterol, and protease inhibitors used to treat retroviral infections such as HIV.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A common example of an irreversible inhibitor that is used as a drug is aspirin, which inhibits the COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes that produce the inflammation messenger prostaglandin.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, the poison cyanide is an irreversible enzyme inhibitor that combines with the copper and iron in the active site of the enzyme cytochrome c oxidase and blocks cellular respiration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] As enzymes are made up of proteins, their actions are sensitive to change in many physio chemical factors such as pH, temperature, substrate concentration, etc.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The following table shows pH optima for various enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes serve a wide variety of functions inside living organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] They are indispensable for signal transduction and cell regulation, often via kinases and phosphatases.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] They also generate movement, with myosin hydrolyzing adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to generate muscle contraction, and also transport cargo around the cell as part of the cytoskeleton.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Other ATPases in the cell membrane are ion pumps involved in active transport.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes are also involved in more exotic functions, such as luciferase generating light in fireflies.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Viruses can also contain enzymes for infecting cells, such as the HIV integrase and reverse transcriptase, or for viral release from cells, like the influenza virus neuraminidase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An important function of enzymes is in the digestive systems of animals.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes such as amylases and proteases break down large molecules (starch or proteins, respectively) into smaller ones, so they can be absorbed by the intestines.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Starch molecules, for example, are too large to be absorbed from the intestine, but enzymes hydrolyze the starch chains into smaller molecules such as maltose and eventually glucose, which can then be absorbed.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Different enzymes digest different food substances.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In ruminants, which have herbivorous diets, microorganisms in the gut produce another enzyme, cellulase, to break down the cellulose cell walls of plant fiber.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Several enzymes can work together in a specific order, creating metabolic pathways.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In a metabolic pathway, one enzyme takes the product of another enzyme as a substrate.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] After the catalytic reaction, the product is then passed on to another enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Sometimes more than one enzyme can catalyze the same reaction in parallel; this can allow more complex regulation: with, for example, a low constant activity provided by one enzyme but an inducible high activity from a second enzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes determine what steps occur in these pathways.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Without enzymes, metabolism would neither progress through the same steps and could not be regulated to serve the needs of the cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Most central metabolic pathways are regulated at a few steps, typically through enzymes whose activity involves the phosphorylation by ATP.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Because this reaction releases so much energy, other reactions that are thermodynamically unfavorable can be coupled to ATP hydrolysis, driving the overall series of linked metabolic reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] There are five main ways that enzyme activity is controlled in the cell.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes can be either activated or inhibited by other molecules.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, the end product(s) of a metabolic pathway are often inhibitors for one of the first enzymes of the pathway (usually the first irreversible step, called committed step), thus regulating the amount of end product made by the pathways.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Such a regulatory mechanism is called a negative feedback mechanism, because the amount of the end product produced is regulated by its own concentration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Negative feedback mechanism can effectively adjust the rate of synthesis of intermediate metabolites according to the demands of the cells.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This helps with effective allocations of materials and energy economy, and it prevents the excess manufacture of end products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Like other homeostatic devices, the control of enzymatic action helps to maintain a stable internal environment in living organisms.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Examples of post-translational modification include phosphorylation, myristoylation and glycosylation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, in the response to insulin, the phosphorylation of multiple enzymes, including glycogen synthase, helps control the synthesis or degradation of glycogen and allows the cell to respond to changes in blood sugar.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Another example of post-translational modification is the cleavage of the polypeptide chain.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Chymotrypsin, a digestive protease, is produced in inactive form as chymotrypsinogen in the pancreas and transported in this form to the stomach where it is activated.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This stops the enzyme from digesting the pancreas or other tissues before it enters the gut.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This type of inactive precursor to an enzyme is known as a zymogen or proenzyme.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme production (transcription and translation of enzyme genes) can be enhanced or diminished by a cell in response to changes in the cell's environment.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This form of gene regulation is called enzyme induction.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, bacteria may become resistant to antibiotics such as penicillin because enzymes called beta-lactamases are induced that hydrolyse the crucial beta-lactam ring within the penicillin molecule.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Another example comes from enzymes in the liver called cytochrome P450 oxidases, which are important in drug metabolism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Induction or inhibition of these enzymes can cause drug interactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzyme levels can also be regulated by changing the rate of enzyme degradation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The opposite of enzyme induction is enzyme repression.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes can be compartmentalized, with different metabolic pathways occurring in different cellular compartments.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, fatty acids are synthesized by one set of enzymes in the cytosol, endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi and used by a different set of enzymes as a source of energy in the mitochondrion, through β-oxidation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In addition, trafficking of the enzyme to different compartments may change the degree of protonation (e.g., the neutral cytoplasm and the acidic lysosome) or oxidative state (e.g., oxidizing periplasm or reducing cytoplasm) which in turn affects enzyme activity.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In contrast to partitioning into membrane bound organelles, enzyme subcellular localisation may also be altered through polymerisation of enzymes into macromolecular cytoplasmic filaments.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In multicellular eukaryotes, cells in different organs and tissues have different patterns of gene expression and therefore have different sets of enzymes (known as isozymes) available for metabolic reactions.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This provides a mechanism for regulating the overall metabolism of the organism.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] For example, hexokinase, the first enzyme in the glycolysis pathway, has a specialized form called glucokinase expressed in the liver and pancreas that has a lower affinity for glucose yet is more sensitive to glucose concentration.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This enzyme is involved in sensing blood sugar and regulating insulin production.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Since the tight control of enzyme activity is essential for homeostasis, any malfunction (mutation, overproduction, underproduction or deletion) of a single critical enzyme can lead to a genetic disease.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] The malfunction of just one type of enzyme out of the thousands of types present in the human body can be fatal.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An example of a fatal genetic disease due to enzyme insufficiency is Tay–Sachs disease, in which patients lack the enzyme hexosaminidase.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] One example of enzyme deficiency is the most common type of phenylketonuria.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Many different single amino acid mutations in the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, which catalyzes the first step in the degradation of phenylalanine, result in build-up of phenylalanine and related products.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Some mutations are in the active site, directly disrupting binding and catalysis, but many are far from the active site and reduce activity by destabilising the protein structure, or affecting correct oligomerisation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This can lead to intellectual disability if the disease is untreated.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Another example is pseudocholinesterase deficiency, in which the body's ability to break down choline ester drugs is impaired.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Oral administration of enzymes can be used to treat some functional enzyme deficiencies, such as pancreatic insufficiency and lactose intolerance.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Another way enzyme malfunctions can cause disease comes from germline mutations in genes coding for DNA repair enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Defects in these enzymes cause cancer because cells are less able to repair mutations in their genomes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This causes a slow accumulation of mutations and results in the development of cancers.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] An example of such a hereditary cancer syndrome is xeroderma pigmentosum, which causes the development of skin cancers in response to even minimal exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Similar to any other protein, enzymes change over time through mutations and sequence divergence.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Given their central role in metabolism, enzyme evolution plays a critical role in adaptation.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] A key question is therefore whether and how enzymes can change their enzymatic activities alongside.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] It is generally accepted that many new enzyme activities have evolved through gene duplication and mutation of the duplicate copies although evolution can also happen without duplication.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In addition, MAP is metal-ion dependent while creatinase is not, hence this property was also lost over time.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Small changes of enzymatic activity are extremely common among enzymes.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] In particular, substrate binding specificity (see above) can easily and quickly change with single amino acid changes in their substrate binding pockets.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] This is frequently seen in the main enzyme classes such as kinases.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Artificial (in vitro) evolution is now commonly used to modify enzyme activity or specificity for industrial applications (see below).
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes are used in the chemical industry and other industrial applications when extremely specific catalysts are required.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] Enzymes in general are limited in the number of reactions they have evolved to catalyze and also by their lack of stability in organic solvents and at high temperatures.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] As a consequence, protein engineering is an active area of research and involves attempts to create new enzymes with novel properties, either through rational design or *in vitro* evolution.
[src:enzymology/enzyme] These efforts have begun to be successful, and a few enzymes have now been designed "from scratch" to catalyze reactions that do not occur in nature.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In biochemistry, **Michaelis–Menten kinetics**, named after Leonor Michaelis and Maud Menten, is the simplest case of enzyme kinetics, applied to enzyme-catalysed reactions involving the transformation of one substrate into one product.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In 1913, Michaelis and Menten expanded on Victor Henri's fundamental equation of enzyme kinetics, which was established in 1902.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] It takes the form of a differential equation describing the reaction rate v (rate of formation of product P, with concentration p ) as a function of a , the concentration of the substrate A (using the symbols recommended by the IUBMB).
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] V , which is often written as $V_{\max }$ , represents the limiting rate approached by the system at saturating substrate concentration for a given enzyme concentration.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The **Michaelis constant** $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ has units of concentration, and for a given reaction is equal to the concentration of substrate at which the reaction rate is half of V .
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Biochemical reactions involving a single substrate are often assumed to follow Michaelis–Menten kinetics, without regard to the model's underlying assumptions.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Only a small proportion of enzyme-catalysed reactions have just one substrate, but the equation still often applies if only one substrate concentration is varied.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The plot of v against a has often been called a "Michaelis–Menten plot", even recently, but this terminology is historically misleading, as Michaelis and Menten did not use such a plot.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Instead, they plotted v against $\log a$ , which has some advantages over the usual ways of plotting Michaelis–Menten data.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] If v is the dependent variable, then it does not distort any experimental errors in v .
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Michaelis and Menten did not attempt to estimate V directly from the limit approached at high $\log a$ , something difficult to do accurately with data obtained with modern techniques, and almost impossible with their data.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Instead they took advantage of the fact that the curve is almost straight in the middle range and has a maximum slope of $0.576V$ i.e. $0.25\ln 10\cdot V$ .
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] With an accurate value of V it was easy to determine $\log K_{\mathrm {m} }$ from the point on the curve corresponding to $0.5V$ .
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] This plot is virtually never used today for estimating V and $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ , but it remains valuable to compare the properties of several enzymes across a broad range of substrate concentrations - such as isoenzymes.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] For example, the four mammalian isoenzymes of hexokinase are half-saturated by glucose at concentrations ranging from about 0.02 mM for hexokinase A (brain hexokinase) to about 50 mM for hexokinase D ("glucokinase", liver hexokinase), spanning a 2500-fold range.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] A conventional (linear) plot would compromise on readability for the high-affinity isoenzyme graphs, but a semi-logarithmic plot allows to read off the kinetic parameters for all isoenzymes.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] A decade before Michaelis and Menten, Victor Henri found that enzyme reactions could be explained by assuming a binding interaction between the enzyme and the substrate.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] His work was taken up by Michaelis and Menten, who investigated the kinetics of invertase, an enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of sucrose into glucose and fructose.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In 1913, they proposed a mathematical model of the reaction.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] It involves an enzyme E binding to a substrate A to form a complex EA that releases a product P regenerating the original form of the enzyme.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] in which $e_{0}$ is the initial enzyme concentration.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The reaction order depends on the relative size of the two terms in the denominator.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] At low substrate concentration $a\ll K_{\mathrm {m} }$ , so that the rate $v={\frac {k_{\mathrm {cat} }e_{0}a}{K_{\mathrm {m} }}}$ varies linearly with substrate concentration a (first-order kinetics in a ).
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] However at higher a , with $a\gg K_{\mathrm {m} }$ , the reaction approaches independence of a (zero-order kinetics in a ), asymptotically approaching the limiting rate $V_{\mathrm {max} }=k_{\mathrm {cat} }e_{0}$ .
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Further addition of substrate would not increase the rate, and the enzyme is said to be saturated.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The Michaelis constant $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ is not affected by the concentration or purity of an enzyme.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Its value depends both on the identity of the enzyme and that of the substrate, as well as conditions such as temperature and pH.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The model is used in a variety of biochemical situations other than enzyme-substrate interaction, including antigen–antibody binding, DNA–DNA hybridization, and protein–protein interaction.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] It can be used to characterize a generic biochemical reaction, in the same way that the Langmuir equation can be used to model generic adsorption of biomolecular species.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] When an empirical equation of this form is applied to microbial growth, it is sometimes called a Monod equation.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Michaelis–Menten kinetics have also been applied to a variety of topics outside of biochemical reactions, including alveolar clearance of dusts, the richness of species pools, clearance of blood alcohol, the photosynthesis-irradiance relationship, and bacterial phage infection.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The equation can also be used to describe the relationship between ion channel conductivity and ligand concentration, and also, for example, to limiting nutrients and phytoplankton growth in the global ocean.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The specificity constant $k_{\text{cat}}/K_{\mathrm {m} }$ (also known as the *catalytic efficiency*) is a measure of how efficiently an enzyme converts a substrate into product.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Although it is the ratio of $k_{\text{cat}}$ and $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ it is a parameter in its own right, more fundamental than $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ .
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Diffusion limited enzymes, such as fumarase, work at the theoretical upper limit of 108 – 1010 M−1s−1, limited by diffusion of substrate into the active site.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The capacity of an enzyme to distinguish between two competing substrates that both follow Michaelis–Menten kinetics depends only on the specificity constant, and not on either $k_{\text{cat}}$ or $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ alone.
[src:enzymology/michaelis-menten-kinetics] and so the ratio of rates depends only on the concentrations of the two substrates and their specificity constants.
